1
00:00:02,085 --> 00:00:04,861
When I first hear
the word "jaws",

2
00:00:04,972 --> 00:00:07,919
you know, I just think
of a period in my life

3
00:00:08,091 --> 00:00:11,868
when I was much younger
than I am right now.

4
00:00:14,031 --> 00:00:16,295
And I think, because I was younger,

5
00:00:16,366 --> 00:00:20,883
I was more courageous, or I was
more stupid. I'm not sure which.

6
00:00:20,988 --> 00:00:24,253
So, when I think of <i>Jaws</i>,
I think about courage and stupidity.

7
00:00:24,358 --> 00:00:27,885
And I think of both of those
things existing underwater.

8
00:00:28,679 --> 00:00:31,364
I had been thinking for years
about a story about a shark

9
00:00:31,465 --> 00:00:32,512
that attacks people,

10
00:00:32,583 --> 00:00:34,984
and what would happen if it
came in and wouldn't go away.

11
00:00:35,052 --> 00:00:36,793
I hadn't done anything with it really.

12
00:00:36,904 --> 00:00:38,429
Then, in 1964,

13
00:00:38,539 --> 00:00:41,156
I read a story about a shark
fisherman off Long Island

14
00:00:41,225 --> 00:00:44,809
who caught a 4,550-pound great white shark

15
00:00:44,912 --> 00:00:46,903
off the beaches of Long Island.

16
00:00:47,014 --> 00:00:51,224
I thought, "Wow! What would happen if one of
these things came in and wouldn't go away?"

17
00:00:51,318 --> 00:00:55,653
Again, I didn't do anything
about it until 1970 or '71,

18
00:00:55,756 --> 00:00:58,487
when a publisher finally said,
"That's an interesting story.

19
00:00:58,592 --> 00:01:01,289
"I'll pay you a couple of
dollars if you'll put it on paper."

20
00:01:01,395 --> 00:01:02,806
So that's how the idea began.

21
00:01:03,814 --> 00:01:06,977
One of the many accidents that
happened with Jaws was the title.

22
00:01:07,050 --> 00:01:08,814
We had no idea of the title.

23
00:01:08,885 --> 00:01:10,501
I had thought for months about titles.

24
00:01:10,604 --> 00:01:13,505
I probably had a hundred.
Some of them were pretentious:

25
00:01:13,607 --> 00:01:16,019
<i>The Stillness in the Water.</i>

26
00:01:16,093 --> 00:01:18,994
<i>A Silence in the Deep.
Leviathan Rising.</i>

27
00:01:19,096 --> 00:01:21,940
A lot of them were Françoise Sagan titles.

28
00:01:22,049 --> 00:01:26,611
You know, terribly
pretentious and very personal.

29
00:01:26,987 --> 00:01:29,638
<i>There were The Jaws of Death
and The Jaws of Leviathan.</i>

30
00:01:29,723 --> 00:01:32,852
They all sounded dramatic or
melodramatic or weird or pretentious.

31
00:01:32,960 --> 00:01:35,474
We came up to 20 minutes
before production.

32
00:01:35,545 --> 00:01:37,639
My editor and I were
lunching at a restaurant

33
00:01:37,748 --> 00:01:39,648
called The Dallas Cowboy in New York.

34
00:01:39,733 --> 00:01:42,851
I said to him, "Look."
This was Tom Condon.

35
00:01:43,737 --> 00:01:46,900
"We cannot agree on a word that we like,

36
00:01:47,007 --> 00:01:48,418
"let alone a title that we like.

37
00:01:48,492 --> 00:01:53,225
"In fact, the only word that we even
think means or says anything is 'jaws.'

38
00:01:53,347 --> 00:01:55,224
"Call the book <i>Jaws</i>".

39
00:01:55,299 --> 00:01:58,132
He said, "What does it
mean?" I said, "I don't know.

40
00:01:58,201 --> 00:02:00,920
"But it's short, it fits on a jacket,

41
00:02:01,021 --> 00:02:03,672
"and it may work."

42
00:02:03,757 --> 00:02:05,088
He said, "Okay, we'll
call the thing Jaws."

43
00:02:06,093 --> 00:02:08,312
At first, nobody knew what they had here,

44
00:02:08,412 --> 00:02:10,073
including myself.
It was a first novel.

45
00:02:10,147 --> 00:02:12,445
It was a first novel about a fish,

46
00:02:12,516 --> 00:02:15,042
and it had no great prospects.

47
00:02:15,118 --> 00:02:17,200
But Tom Condon, the editor at Doubleday,

48
00:02:17,304 --> 00:02:21,104
sensed that there was more here
than just a first novel about a fish.

49
00:02:21,208 --> 00:02:22,369
So it was sent out

50
00:02:22,476 --> 00:02:24,990
to the Book-of-the-Month Club
and The Literary Guild

51
00:02:25,062 --> 00:02:27,724
and Bantam and other paperback houses.

52
00:02:27,798 --> 00:02:30,574
The first response was

53
00:02:30,684 --> 00:02:33,699
from the Book-of-the-Month Club,

54
00:02:33,787 --> 00:02:38,475
which made it an "A" book, meaning
it is selected for a main selection

55
00:02:38,542 --> 00:02:40,977
or it is in the running
for a main selection.

56
00:02:41,078 --> 00:02:43,911
Suddenly people began to think,
whoops, we may have something more here

57
00:02:43,980 --> 00:02:46,176
than just a first novel,
which nobody will read,

58
00:02:46,249 --> 00:02:49,230
and a first novel about a
fish, which who cares less.

59
00:02:49,986 --> 00:02:53,115
<i>Then the Reader's Digest
selected it as a selection</i>

60
00:02:53,190 --> 00:02:56,922
and the Book-of-the-Month Club
made it an "A" book, main selection.

61
00:02:56,993 --> 00:03:00,679
Then Bantam bought it for what
was then an enormous sum of money,

62
00:03:00,731 --> 00:03:02,995
$575,000.

63
00:03:05,419 --> 00:03:07,729
Then it went out to the movie auctions.

64
00:03:07,821 --> 00:03:11,951
And, in those days, we're
now talking many years ago,

65
00:03:12,059 --> 00:03:16,144
it went to Zanuck and Brown
at Universal for $150,000.

66
00:03:16,213 --> 00:03:18,261
Which was, to me, the moon.

67
00:03:18,365 --> 00:03:21,892
I had no money at all.
I had, in the bank, $300.

68
00:03:22,119 --> 00:03:25,896
Both Dick Zanuck and I
saw or heard about the book

69
00:03:26,006 --> 00:03:27,906
at identical times.

70
00:03:28,008 --> 00:03:31,854
I heard about it from a small
card in the fiction department

71
00:03:31,928 --> 00:03:35,705
of <i>Cosmopolitan</i>, edited by my wife,
Helen Gurley Brown,

72
00:03:35,816 --> 00:03:39,446
which gave a brief description of the
plot of this novel by Peter Benchley,

73
00:03:39,553 --> 00:03:41,794
and then said, "Might make a good movie."

74
00:03:41,872 --> 00:03:44,022
We both read it overnight,

75
00:03:44,124 --> 00:03:47,606
got on the phone with each
other the next morning and said,

76
00:03:47,677 --> 00:03:50,544
"We don't know how we can possibly do it."

77
00:03:50,614 --> 00:03:54,983
But we decided we must
have this, whatever it takes.

78
00:03:55,051 --> 00:03:57,986
This is the most exciting
thing we've ever read,

79
00:03:58,054 --> 00:04:01,638
and we'll figure out later
how we can make it.

80
00:04:01,742 --> 00:04:03,904
Had we read it twice, in my opinion,

81
00:04:03,994 --> 00:04:05,644
we never would have made <i>Jaws</i>.

82
00:04:05,746 --> 00:04:10,377
Because anybody with a
modicum of production knowledge

83
00:04:10,484 --> 00:04:13,419
would know there was no way to get a man…

84
00:04:13,487 --> 00:04:16,218
Get a shark

85
00:04:16,323 --> 00:04:19,270
to leap on the stern of a
small boat and swallow a man.

86
00:04:19,342 --> 00:04:20,639
How were we going to do this?

87
00:04:20,710 --> 00:04:22,644
Were we going to do it in animation?

88
00:04:22,712 --> 00:04:25,909
Who was going to do this?
We never thought about it.

89
00:04:25,982 --> 00:04:27,541
We just loved the book.

90
00:04:27,617 --> 00:04:29,244
We thought it would make
a very good movie.

91
00:04:29,436 --> 00:04:34,067
The deal was subject to a meeting

92
00:04:34,174 --> 00:04:35,505
with Mr. Benchley.

93
00:04:35,609 --> 00:04:37,941
Who we'd never met before, actually.

94
00:04:38,028 --> 00:04:41,396
And the agency also very much wanted us

95
00:04:41,465 --> 00:04:45,663
to tie a director of theirs,
one of their clients,

96
00:04:45,735 --> 00:04:49,763
into this whole package.

97
00:04:49,840 --> 00:04:53,868
So we had agreed to… I'm not
going to mention this person's name

98
00:04:53,944 --> 00:04:56,572
because this is not a flattering story.

99
00:04:56,646 --> 00:04:59,991
But we had agreed, in our anxiety,

100
00:05:00,100 --> 00:05:03,411
to secure the rights to the book

101
00:05:03,487 --> 00:05:05,785
to put on this person as a director.

102
00:05:05,856 --> 00:05:08,848
There was a director, and I
really don't remember who it was,

103
00:05:08,942 --> 00:05:13,596
who kept saying, "I've always
wanted to make a movie about a whale."

104
00:05:15,382 --> 00:05:17,965
At the end of it, Zanuck
said, "That's the end of that."

105
00:05:18,034 --> 00:05:21,083
When the director who
was going to direct a whale

106
00:05:21,188 --> 00:05:23,634
was vanquished from our sight…

107
00:05:23,707 --> 00:05:27,337
And here was Steven
Spielberg. Director, filmmaker…

108
00:05:27,410 --> 00:05:30,607
Sugar/and Express,
right within sight of us.

109
00:05:30,680 --> 00:05:34,298
Steven actually… And there
are many versions of this.

110
00:05:34,401 --> 00:05:36,927
Steven will tell you his,
probably the true one.

111
00:05:37,037 --> 00:05:41,782
I just remember seeing a very
large, you know, block of pages

112
00:05:41,992 --> 00:05:45,656
that said Jaws on it, and I
didn't know what that meant.

113
00:05:45,729 --> 00:05:48,994
What was Jaws?
Was it about a dentist?

114
00:05:49,065 --> 00:05:51,841
Was this, you know, was it…

115
00:05:51,952 --> 00:05:54,364
Because <i>Jaws</i> did not have a…

116
00:05:54,437 --> 00:05:56,929
It was not in the national
consciousness at the time.

117
00:05:57,007 --> 00:05:59,374
It was just a word. It was
kind of an unusual word.

118
00:05:59,442 --> 00:06:02,935
I remember borrowing a
copy to read over the weekend

119
00:06:03,013 --> 00:06:06,313
and discovering I was
completely uninformed,

120
00:06:06,383 --> 00:06:11,230
not knowing that it was a
book about a great white shark.

121
00:06:11,338 --> 00:06:14,399
A predator off a beach

122
00:06:14,491 --> 00:06:18,359
in a kind of, you know,
Cape Cod-esque town.

123
00:06:19,279 --> 00:06:21,179
I had no idea this was about to become

124
00:06:21,281 --> 00:06:24,410
one of the best-selling
books in the nation.

125
00:06:24,501 --> 00:06:27,960
I read it, and I said to myself, "Wow,

126
00:06:28,038 --> 00:06:29,972
"this is just like a movie I just made

127
00:06:30,040 --> 00:06:34,841
<i>"about a truck and a hapless driver,</i>

128
00:06:34,928 --> 00:06:37,022
<i>"called Duel."</i>

129
00:06:37,213 --> 00:06:40,706
Of course I'm young and
I'm stupid and I'm saying,

130
00:06:40,784 --> 00:06:42,627
"Duel. Gee, that has four words…

131
00:06:42,736 --> 00:06:45,785
"Duel has four letters
and Jaws has four letters,

132
00:06:45,855 --> 00:06:48,802
"and they're both about these leviathans

133
00:06:48,909 --> 00:06:52,209
"Preying upon everyman."

134
00:06:52,312 --> 00:06:56,328
I saw such a comparison between Duel,

135
00:06:56,399 --> 00:07:01,280
which I <i>had done previous to
Sugar land Express, and Jaws,</i>

136
00:07:01,388 --> 00:07:05,120
I said to myself, "This is kind of the
sequel to <i>Duel,</i> only it's on the water."

137
00:07:05,225 --> 00:07:09,640
I got very interested in it because,
coincidentally, the producers of Jaws

138
00:07:09,713 --> 00:07:14,025
had just been my producers on
my first feature, Sugar/and <i>Express,</i>

139
00:07:14,134 --> 00:07:16,182
Dick Zanuck and David Brown.

140
00:07:16,252 --> 00:07:18,812
I asked them if this was
something I could direct next.

141
00:07:19,823 --> 00:07:23,157
The first thing Dick Zanuck
and David Brown said to me is,

142
00:07:23,259 --> 00:07:25,068
"We want to get rid of the back stories.

143
00:07:25,161 --> 00:07:28,620
"We want to make this
an A-Z adventure story.

144
00:07:28,715 --> 00:07:31,582
"We do not want to have
any of that involvement

145
00:07:31,685 --> 00:07:35,303
"with a romance between
Hooper and Mrs. Brody.

146
00:07:35,372 --> 00:07:38,490
"We don't want to talk about the
Mafia or about anything like that.

147
00:07:38,575 --> 00:07:41,784
"We want to make this a
straight-line adventure story."

148
00:07:41,895 --> 00:07:45,058
Peter Benchley did a very
good adaptation of his own novel.

149
00:07:45,165 --> 00:07:48,863
Then Peter kind of turned
it over to me and said,

150
00:07:48,969 --> 00:07:51,779
"Here it is.
Do with it what you want."

151
00:07:51,855 --> 00:07:54,586
At that point, I didn't quite
know what to do with it,

152
00:07:54,658 --> 00:07:57,059
'cause it wasn't the movie
I wanted to make next.

153
00:07:57,127 --> 00:08:01,371
I quite didn't know the movie I
wanted to make from the novel Jaws.

154
00:08:01,464 --> 00:08:04,240
I knew about the third act,
and I knew about the first act.

155
00:08:04,351 --> 00:08:08,913
I just didn't know about the second
act, which was going to be a 60-page act.

156
00:08:09,022 --> 00:08:11,673
I remember sitting down
and writing the script myself.

157
00:08:11,758 --> 00:08:14,557
Doing an entire draft
myself, from beginning to end.

158
00:08:14,661 --> 00:08:16,652
Which I haven't shown to very many people.

159
00:08:16,763 --> 00:08:20,461
And I don't even think I have it anymore.

160
00:08:20,567 --> 00:08:23,559
But I remember a few
of the scenes did survive

161
00:08:23,670 --> 00:08:25,729
the movie, and wound up in the film.

162
00:08:25,839 --> 00:08:28,570
But it was more of an exercise for me

163
00:08:28,675 --> 00:08:32,725
to become familiar with what
I wanted Jaws to become.

164
00:08:32,796 --> 00:08:35,310
It was an exercise
that was very beneficial

165
00:08:35,415 --> 00:08:37,383
because I suddenly
had a vision of the film

166
00:08:37,484 --> 00:08:40,602
even though I didn't
possess the skills to write it.

167
00:08:40,754 --> 00:08:44,657
David Brown and Dick Zanuck both suggested

168
00:08:44,758 --> 00:08:46,704
that I go to Howard Sackler,

169
00:08:46,793 --> 00:08:48,124
<i>who had written The Great White Hope.</i>

170
00:08:48,228 --> 00:08:52,597
We went from Peter Benchley to a
writer by the name of Howard Sackler.

171
00:08:52,699 --> 00:08:57,603
Who was a Pulitzer
Prize-winning playwright

172
00:08:57,721 --> 00:08:59,746
<i>who wrote The Great White Hope.</i>

173
00:08:59,823 --> 00:09:03,555
He had been working
on something else for us.

174
00:09:03,626 --> 00:09:07,608
He also was an expert scuba diver,

175
00:09:07,714 --> 00:09:10,024
and scuba dived all around the world.

176
00:09:10,100 --> 00:09:13,195
Was very familiar, as is
Benchley, by the way…

177
00:09:13,269 --> 00:09:15,397
Great diver.

178
00:09:15,472 --> 00:09:19,204
Very familiar with sharks
and underwater activity.

179
00:09:19,275 --> 00:09:23,155
Howard Sackler specifically
asked not to have credit.

180
00:09:23,263 --> 00:09:26,528
He only had a limited time
to give to the film.

181
00:09:26,633 --> 00:09:29,068
Therefore, he said, "I don't want credit."

182
00:09:29,169 --> 00:09:31,479
But he was, I think…

183
00:09:31,554 --> 00:09:34,899
Spielberg would say he was very important

184
00:09:35,008 --> 00:09:39,275
in that terrible phrase
of motion picture-making:

185
00:09:39,379 --> 00:09:41,746
He "broke the back of the story."

186
00:09:41,848 --> 00:09:44,328
Sackler broke the back of
the movie and got me to say,

187
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:46,801
"Yes, I'll make this movie
next. I'm committing."

188
00:09:46,870 --> 00:09:49,896
Then came something
that's not been recorded

189
00:09:49,973 --> 00:09:51,657
in the history of Jaws.

190
00:09:51,758 --> 00:09:54,341
The Screen Actors Guild contract

191
00:09:54,410 --> 00:09:57,755
was about to expire at
the end of June of that year.

192
00:09:57,864 --> 00:10:02,244
It could have been 1973,
perhaps, whenever the year was.

193
00:10:02,318 --> 00:10:06,733
The studio decreed that
no movie would be started

194
00:10:06,840 --> 00:10:11,152
that could not be finished
by June 30 of that year,

195
00:10:11,244 --> 00:10:12,894
because they didn't want to be struck.

196
00:10:12,962 --> 00:10:15,795
That is, that photography was completed.

197
00:10:16,800 --> 00:10:20,680
Steven Spielberg, Richard Zanuck
and I met at the Bel-Air Hotel.

198
00:10:20,787 --> 00:10:23,563
And Steven said,
"I don't have a script yet.

199
00:10:23,640 --> 00:10:26,018
"You're asking me to
start this movie in April?"

200
00:10:26,126 --> 00:10:29,278
Whenever it was, I don't
know, maybe this was February.

201
00:10:29,345 --> 00:10:31,791
He said, "I don't have a script."

202
00:10:32,899 --> 00:10:35,869
And I said, "Who can we get?"

203
00:10:35,969 --> 00:10:38,404
He said, "There's a man
named Carl Gottlieb.

204
00:10:38,505 --> 00:10:40,234
"I'm thinking about him for the movie.“

205
00:10:40,356 --> 00:10:42,768
I was hired first as an actor because,

206
00:10:42,876 --> 00:10:46,176
if I was going to be on
the set, I could at least help

207
00:10:46,279 --> 00:10:50,864
in the improvisations and crowd scenes
and finding stuff to do in the moment,

208
00:10:50,934 --> 00:10:54,768
which had been my job on stage
at the Committee as an improviser.

209
00:10:54,838 --> 00:10:57,239
Steven thought that
would be useful to the film

210
00:10:57,307 --> 00:10:59,674
to be able to go with the flow

211
00:10:59,742 --> 00:11:02,086
and find things on the set and improvise.

212
00:11:02,195 --> 00:11:06,257
In fact, some of the best lines in
the film are improvised by the actors

213
00:11:06,366 --> 00:11:08,733
based on their characters in the script.

214
00:11:08,835 --> 00:11:13,318
I asked Carl Gottlieb, who was a
friend of mine, to come in to do a polish

215
00:11:13,389 --> 00:11:16,438
and to actually help me…

216
00:11:16,543 --> 00:11:18,591
If I wanted to improvise scenes,

217
00:11:18,661 --> 00:11:22,256
Carl would be there to help organize
the improvisation and put it on paper.

218
00:11:22,332 --> 00:11:26,018
I said that we have a
chance to make a movie

219
00:11:26,119 --> 00:11:30,067
that's going to do for the ocean
what the shower scene did to Psycho,

220
00:11:30,139 --> 00:11:34,337
in terms of affecting a generation
with, kind of, a fear of the water.

221
00:11:34,410 --> 00:11:37,129
To this day, when people
come up to me and learn

222
00:11:37,230 --> 00:11:41,758
that I worked on the screenplay
of Jaws, and talk to me about it,

223
00:11:41,868 --> 00:11:45,566
inevitably, the first thing they say is,
"That summer I didn't go swimming."

224
00:11:45,672 --> 00:11:48,369
Or "I've been afraid of the
water ever since that movie."

225
00:11:48,458 --> 00:11:50,870
Or "I'm always thinking of
sharks when I go swimming.

226
00:11:50,977 --> 00:11:54,242
"In Hawaii, I don't go swimming
at all." I hear that to this day.

227
00:11:54,347 --> 00:11:55,826
So, surprisingly enough,

228
00:11:55,899 --> 00:11:59,733
that was my first reaction
to the script and the story.

229
00:11:59,802 --> 00:12:02,931
It's the thing that appears
to have carried through,

230
00:12:03,006 --> 00:12:06,055
and is one of the overwhelming
impressions that we made.

231
00:12:06,159 --> 00:12:08,150
It's, you know, become popular culture.

232
00:12:09,162 --> 00:12:12,678
When you do a straight-line
adventure film like <i>Jaws,</i>

233
00:12:12,749 --> 00:12:15,912
anything that doesn't contribute
to the suspense or the humanity

234
00:12:16,002 --> 00:12:18,130
or the horror, has to go.

235
00:12:18,238 --> 00:12:22,505
I wanted to introduce
Quint, not in his boat,

236
00:12:22,609 --> 00:12:25,237
<i>laughing at all the yahoos on shore,</i>

237
00:12:25,345 --> 00:12:28,246
<i>in that one little visual
where the Orca goes by</i>

238
00:12:28,348 --> 00:12:30,612
<i>with Quint laughing and chuckling</i>

239
00:12:30,717 --> 00:12:33,402
<i>at the tiger shark that
obviously isn't the predator</i>

240
00:12:33,469 --> 00:12:35,961
<i>that's been killing all
the people in the vicinity.</i>

241
00:12:36,039 --> 00:12:38,258
I had another thing that
I'd written in my script.

242
00:12:38,358 --> 00:12:40,941
As you recall, I wrote
an entire script of Jaws

243
00:12:41,027 --> 00:12:43,678
after Benchley and before Sackler.

244
00:12:43,746 --> 00:12:46,727
And this was one of the
scenes that I had written.

245
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:52,004
That Robert Shaw, or Quint, is in a
movie theater watching <i>Moby Dick</i>

246
00:12:53,122 --> 00:12:55,272
on the island of Amity
at the local movie house.

247
00:12:55,375 --> 00:12:58,208
He's laughing all the way
through it. He can't stop laughing.

248
00:12:58,311 --> 00:13:02,544
It's so silly, the mechanical white
whale, Ahab with his big harpoon,

249
00:13:02,649 --> 00:13:05,994
stabbing the whale as
he's lashed to the belly,

250
00:13:06,069 --> 00:13:09,482
and the whale sounding and
coming up again, and he's still…

251
00:13:09,589 --> 00:13:12,217
This mechanical figure is still sticking

252
00:13:12,325 --> 00:13:14,191
the mechanical harpoon in the whale.

253
00:13:14,294 --> 00:13:16,342
I just had Quint laughing hysterically.

254
00:13:16,429 --> 00:13:20,195
Laughing so hard
and so sort of maliciously

255
00:13:20,300 --> 00:13:23,759
that people get up and start
leaving the theater until he's all alone,

256
00:13:23,870 --> 00:13:26,919
and his laughter can be
heard right down the street.

257
00:13:26,990 --> 00:13:28,469
That was in my script.

258
00:13:28,558 --> 00:13:32,472
But in trying to get the rights to Moby
<i>Dick,</i> which Gregory Peck controlled,

259
00:13:32,562 --> 00:13:35,930
Greg wasn't opposed

260
00:13:35,999 --> 00:13:40,129
to the use of that scene that way in <i>Jaws</i>.

261
00:13:40,203 --> 00:13:43,764
He just claimed that he wasn't
really proud of <i>Moby Dick.</i>

262
00:13:43,840 --> 00:13:48,004
It was not the proudest
moment in his body of work,

263
00:13:48,094 --> 00:13:51,860
and just didn't really want
us to either make fun of it

264
00:13:51,948 --> 00:13:54,007
or just include it at all in the movie.

265
00:13:54,100 --> 00:13:56,410
So we could never get
the rights to use <i>Moby Dick.</i>

266
00:13:56,486 --> 00:13:57,965
It's part of the film making process.

267
00:13:58,071 --> 00:14:00,415
You write stuff you think you want to see.

268
00:14:00,490 --> 00:14:04,074
Then you sit down and analyze
it, for all kinds of reasons,

269
00:14:04,177 --> 00:14:07,545
for dramatic reasons,
it's hard to fit them in.

270
00:14:07,647 --> 00:14:11,800
Or for production reasons, or
sometimes they're redundant.

271
00:14:11,868 --> 00:14:16,078
For example, the guys on the
pier, one of them losing his leg.

272
00:14:16,189 --> 00:14:19,033
Well, we have a guy losing
his leg elsewhere in the film.

273
00:14:19,125 --> 00:14:22,823
So, it was, you know,
one lost leg too many.

274
00:14:22,929 --> 00:14:25,899
It would have given
the shark a matched set.

275
00:14:25,982 --> 00:14:30,727
For us, it was not <i>as</i> useful to the
plot. It would have been repetitive.

276
00:14:30,837 --> 00:14:33,351
I had this idea that
there's a harbormaster,

277
00:14:33,423 --> 00:14:35,050
and he's in his little shack.

278
00:14:35,141 --> 00:14:37,542
There's all these sailboats.
It's night.

279
00:14:37,627 --> 00:14:40,369
There's about 20 sailboats
with just their masts sticking up.

280
00:14:40,480 --> 00:14:42,471
The harbormaster in my script,

281
00:14:42,582 --> 00:14:43,890
he's watching a movie with Glenn Ford

282
00:14:43,966 --> 00:14:45,741
<i>called Don't Go Near the Water,</i>

283
00:14:45,852 --> 00:14:47,900
which I thought film
aficionados would get off on.

284
00:14:47,970 --> 00:14:50,655
They'd say, "Clever. He's
watching Don't Go Near the Water."

285
00:14:50,757 --> 00:14:53,692
Meanwhile, in the back you
notice, as he's watching this movie,

286
00:14:53,793 --> 00:14:56,319
one mast starts to go like this.

287
00:14:56,496 --> 00:14:59,909
Then the ship next to it,
that mast goes like this.

288
00:14:59,982 --> 00:15:03,111
Then the third mast goes
like this, and the fourth mast…

289
00:15:03,186 --> 00:15:06,850
Until all of a sudden you see,
in sequential order,

290
00:15:06,923 --> 00:15:11,702
something is traveling beneath
the keels of all these sailboats,

291
00:15:11,811 --> 00:15:13,506
and all the masts are moving,

292
00:15:13,613 --> 00:15:15,126
getting closer to the harbormaster.

293
00:15:15,198 --> 00:15:19,715
As the harbormaster goes down to
clean out his coffeepot in the harbor.

294
00:15:19,819 --> 00:15:22,049
As he gets down there
to clean out his coffeepot,

295
00:15:22,155 --> 00:15:24,135
he, of course, is taken by the shark.

296
00:15:24,207 --> 00:15:26,426
That was a scene that
was in my original script

297
00:15:26,526 --> 00:15:29,587
that we just basically
couldn't afford to shoot.

298
00:15:29,679 --> 00:15:32,523
In its place, I wrote this other scene,

299
00:15:33,015 --> 00:15:35,109
which was also in my original script,

300
00:15:35,201 --> 00:15:39,001
that slid over to this one,
which is the pier.

301
00:15:39,105 --> 00:15:42,587
The two fishermen who
take the Sunday pot roast

302
00:15:43,376 --> 00:15:47,688
and a huge chain and a large
Texas Chainsaw Massacre-style hook,

303
00:15:48,181 --> 00:15:50,616
and toss it into the current
and the tide takes it out.

304
00:15:50,700 --> 00:15:53,749
Of course, the shark takes the
bait and the pier comes right off.

305
00:15:53,853 --> 00:15:56,447
<i>The guy comes off the pier.</i>

306
00:15:56,556 --> 00:16:00,265
<i>The reason I wanted the scene
in the movie was for one shot.</i>

307
00:16:00,343 --> 00:16:03,461
<i>Not seeing the shark was important
to me because it was scarier.</i>

308
00:16:03,563 --> 00:16:07,864
<i>In my opinion, seeing the pier
going off, stopping and turning,</i>

309
00:16:07,984 --> 00:16:10,863
<i>and the pier itself coming
back for the swimmer…</i>

310
00:16:22,098 --> 00:16:24,647
Charlie, take my word
for it, don't look back!

311
00:16:24,734 --> 00:16:26,316
Swim, Charlie!

312
00:16:26,419 --> 00:16:30,117
I've heard that Steven wanted to have
the old couple from Sugar/and Express,

313
00:16:30,223 --> 00:16:34,854
whose car was stolen,
turn up in their car in Amity.

314
00:16:44,070 --> 00:16:45,185
What's the story?

315
00:16:45,271 --> 00:16:47,968
The missus and I just had
our car taken by an ex-con.

316
00:16:48,074 --> 00:16:49,553
Claimed he was a workingman.

317
00:16:49,642 --> 00:16:51,121
Was it a green Buick?

318
00:16:51,244 --> 00:16:52,962
Seafoam green, 1956.

319
00:16:53,029 --> 00:16:55,339
Road master, B-O-W-44.
Stole!

320
00:16:55,448 --> 00:16:58,713
- You Alvin T. Nocker of New Frankfort?
- Oh, yes, sir.

321
00:16:58,818 --> 00:17:00,195
Now you're talking.
Yes, sir.

322
00:17:00,286 --> 00:17:01,651
You just stay put.

323
00:17:04,824 --> 00:17:06,815
I wanted them to be passing through Amity.

324
00:17:06,926 --> 00:17:09,896
Maybe even going to the beach
and spreading out a picnic blanket.

325
00:17:09,996 --> 00:17:11,873
Even fantasizing and saying…

326
00:17:11,948 --> 00:17:14,679
Perhaps Mr. Nocker blows up an inner tube,

327
00:17:14,834 --> 00:17:18,145
and we get the idea that maybe
he'll go out in the water with his wife.

328
00:17:18,221 --> 00:17:20,462
I thought, "This movie's too hard to make.

329
00:17:20,573 --> 00:17:23,474
"I've got to stop making
it harder on myself."

330
00:17:23,793 --> 00:17:26,012
We thought that

331
00:17:26,112 --> 00:17:30,276
to legitimize the movie,

332
00:17:30,383 --> 00:17:31,794
there should be

333
00:17:31,867 --> 00:17:36,384
some real shark footage in the picture.

334
00:17:36,706 --> 00:17:40,973
We had anticipated having
much more in the picture

335
00:17:41,077 --> 00:17:44,274
than actually ended up being in it.

336
00:17:44,347 --> 00:17:48,614
So we sent a second unit
down to Australia.

337
00:17:48,701 --> 00:17:53,389
Ron and Valerie Taylor were
engaged in order to shoot

338
00:17:53,456 --> 00:17:56,403
<i>real shark footage off of Australia.</i>

339
00:17:56,993 --> 00:17:59,894
<i>Which they were well experienced at doing.</i>

340
00:18:02,365 --> 00:18:05,676
My recollection is they were
involved with Peter Gimbel.

341
00:18:05,785 --> 00:18:08,117
I may be wrong about that.
<i>Blue</i> Water, <i>White</i> Death.

342
00:18:08,204 --> 00:18:10,298
<i>Blue Water, White Death was and</i> is

343
00:18:10,373 --> 00:18:13,422
the finest documentary
ever made on sharks.

344
00:18:13,526 --> 00:18:16,120
It was done by Peter Gimbel

345
00:18:16,212 --> 00:18:19,045
with Ron and Valerie Taylor
and Stan Waterman.

346
00:18:19,115 --> 00:18:22,642
They went with Rodney Fox
down south in Australia,

347
00:18:22,735 --> 00:18:24,430
and they found the great white shark,

348
00:18:24,537 --> 00:18:27,655
and they did a documentary that
stands alone 20-some years later

349
00:18:27,740 --> 00:18:30,050
as the pinnacle of shark documentaries,

350
00:18:30,126 --> 00:18:31,389
no matter what else has been done.

351
00:18:31,494 --> 00:18:33,690
The producers asked Peter Gimbel

352
00:18:33,763 --> 00:18:37,461
if he would do the camera work on <i>Jaws,</i>

353
00:18:37,566 --> 00:18:41,662
and Peter said, "No, I won't do the
camera work, but I'll direct for you."

354
00:18:41,754 --> 00:18:45,816
We said, "But, Peter, you've only
directed sharks in a documentary.

355
00:18:45,925 --> 00:18:48,235
"We're going to have actors."

356
00:18:48,311 --> 00:18:50,143
He said, "I don't care.
I want to direct."

357
00:18:50,246 --> 00:18:53,307
So Peter Gimbel never got
to be associated with Jaws.

358
00:18:53,416 --> 00:18:55,100
We joked about it many times.

359
00:18:55,201 --> 00:18:58,796
Peter said, "Sorry, I can't
work on the production for you,

360
00:18:58,888 --> 00:19:01,801
"but there are a couple in
Australia, Ron and Valerie Taylor,

361
00:19:01,891 --> 00:19:04,155
"who have experience
with the great white shark.

362
00:19:04,260 --> 00:19:06,160
"Why don't you contact them?"

363
00:19:06,228 --> 00:19:10,256
Sure enough, Universal
Pictures contacted Valerie and I.

364
00:19:10,383 --> 00:19:13,546
I said, "Yes, I think we can
do the underwater shooting

365
00:19:13,653 --> 00:19:16,167
"of live sharks in South Australia."

366
00:19:16,238 --> 00:19:19,264
So they flew me to America,

367
00:19:19,342 --> 00:19:23,472
and I spoke with Steven
Spielberg and Joe Alves,

368
00:19:23,546 --> 00:19:25,560
and met the production team over there,

369
00:19:25,665 --> 00:19:28,134
and explained what I thought we could do

370
00:19:28,234 --> 00:19:30,669
with the real, live great white sharks.

371
00:19:31,087 --> 00:19:35,285
But I explained that our sharks
were only about 14 feet long,

372
00:19:35,358 --> 00:19:38,817
whereas Jaws was about 26 feet long.

373
00:19:38,928 --> 00:19:41,306
I had this idea of doing a miniature cage

374
00:19:41,414 --> 00:19:44,679
and putting a little person into a midget…

375
00:19:44,784 --> 00:19:47,560
Into a miniature cage.

376
00:19:47,636 --> 00:19:50,082
And taking the little person…

377
00:19:51,273 --> 00:19:54,584
That would have effectively
scaled the shark up

378
00:19:54,694 --> 00:19:57,573
and added another, you know, nine feet

379
00:19:57,646 --> 00:19:59,671
to the overall length of the shark.

380
00:19:59,749 --> 00:20:01,740
That kind of made sense to me.

381
00:20:01,834 --> 00:20:06,385
But I was looking for a little person
who was in scale with the cage

382
00:20:06,472 --> 00:20:09,373
and was interviewing
a number of little people.

383
00:20:10,593 --> 00:20:14,120
I remember this tenacious gentleman

384
00:20:14,230 --> 00:20:17,427
who came in to see me, bleeding.

385
00:20:17,500 --> 00:20:18,968
I said, "Why are you bleeding?"

386
00:20:19,034 --> 00:20:22,334
He said, "I was afraid I was going
to be late. I really want this job.

387
00:20:22,405 --> 00:20:25,921
"I got into a traffic accident in
front of the main gate at Universal."

388
00:20:26,025 --> 00:20:28,892
I said, "You did?" He said, "I
came here to have the meeting."

389
00:20:28,978 --> 00:20:31,140
I said, "Did you leave
the scene of the accident?

390
00:20:31,247 --> 00:20:32,897
"You're not supposed to."

391
00:20:32,982 --> 00:20:34,814
We sent him back to the accident

392
00:20:34,884 --> 00:20:37,364
to fill out the report with the police.

393
00:20:37,470 --> 00:20:40,519
I remember I was thinking,
"What a brave man."

394
00:20:40,790 --> 00:20:43,839
And, "He really wants this job."

395
00:20:43,893 --> 00:20:45,372
And I was…

396
00:20:45,478 --> 00:20:48,061
I was young and courageous
and stupid, and I hired him.

397
00:20:48,164 --> 00:20:50,064
His name was Carl Rizzo.

398
00:20:50,166 --> 00:20:54,330
Hollywood sent us this little
man, and he couldn't dive.

399
00:20:54,487 --> 00:20:57,115
He had spent most
of his life riding horses,

400
00:20:57,223 --> 00:20:59,749
doubling for children in
films like National Velvet.

401
00:20:59,859 --> 00:21:01,975
He'd doubled for Elizabeth Taylor.

402
00:21:03,646 --> 00:21:06,547
We had to take him out
and stuff him into a cage

403
00:21:06,615 --> 00:21:09,016
and dangle him into
the cold, southern ocean,

404
00:21:09,084 --> 00:21:13,248
and have big, huge, monstrous
sharks swimming around him.

405
00:21:13,806 --> 00:21:16,548
He was very much afraid,
and we had a lot of difficulty

406
00:21:16,625 --> 00:21:20,186
getting him into the cage, which
is probably quite understandable.

407
00:21:23,098 --> 00:21:24,862
<i>We did have two dummies,</i>

408
00:21:24,934 --> 00:21:27,244
<i>because we were supposed
to have somebody in the cage</i>

409
00:21:27,353 --> 00:21:29,151
<i>when the shark broke it up.</i>

410
00:21:55,331 --> 00:21:57,072
<i>But we had Carl, and he was much better.</i>

411
00:21:57,183 --> 00:22:00,130
<i>He looked better in the
cage, and moved around a bit.</i>

412
00:22:08,077 --> 00:22:10,705
We'd been working for about a week,

413
00:22:10,880 --> 00:22:14,760
and we still hadn't got the shots

414
00:22:14,867 --> 00:22:16,983
of the shark attacking the cage.

415
00:22:17,052 --> 00:22:20,989
They don't normally do that.
They'd rather attack a bait.

416
00:22:22,625 --> 00:22:25,139
There were three sharks
in the area at the time,

417
00:22:25,244 --> 00:22:27,292
and two of them were fairly timid,

418
00:22:27,363 --> 00:22:30,412
<i>but one of them came in
and he was a big, strong shark,</i>

419
00:22:30,516 --> 00:22:32,257
<i>and he swam around.</i>

420
00:22:32,334 --> 00:22:35,736
We had the small cage, the
half-size cage, hanging on a bridle

421
00:22:35,804 --> 00:22:38,853
attached to a winch
on the deck of the skippy.

422
00:22:38,958 --> 00:22:43,270
He swam over it and got
his nose caught in the bridle

423
00:22:43,345 --> 00:22:46,895
and tried to swim forward
and became trapped.

424
00:22:47,600 --> 00:22:49,432
When a white shark is trapped,

425
00:22:49,535 --> 00:22:51,913
it goes crazy, and
that's exactly what he did.

426
00:22:52,004 --> 00:22:54,405
Ron was filming underwater,

427
00:22:54,490 --> 00:22:58,449
and actually, that's how we
got that footage, and they used it.

428
00:22:58,561 --> 00:23:01,724
They wanted someone
in the cage at the time,

429
00:23:01,830 --> 00:23:03,491
but there was nobody in the cage.

430
00:23:03,566 --> 00:23:05,864
So they changed the script

431
00:23:05,935 --> 00:23:08,814
to suit that sequence
because it was so dramatic.

432
00:23:45,874 --> 00:23:49,139
<i>It looked like the
shark was destroying the cage,</i>

433
00:23:49,778 --> 00:23:51,121
and, in fact, it did.

434
00:23:51,230 --> 00:23:52,914
It did a lot of damage to the cage.

435
00:23:52,982 --> 00:23:55,349
It broke it away from the small boat,

436
00:23:55,417 --> 00:23:58,102
<i>and the whole lot came
tumbling down past me</i>

437
00:23:58,187 --> 00:23:59,928
<i>and crashed down onto the bottom.</i>

438
00:24:00,789 --> 00:24:05,067
<i>That was the scariest thing, I
think, I've ever seen underwater</i>

439
00:24:05,361 --> 00:24:07,238
<i>because the whole lot was crashing.</i>

440
00:24:07,346 --> 00:24:10,088
<i>I could see the shark and the cage</i>

441
00:24:10,165 --> 00:24:12,213
<i>all crashing around down on the bottom,</i>

442
00:24:12,318 --> 00:24:14,309
<i>and I thought we were
going to lose the cage.</i>

443
00:24:14,420 --> 00:24:17,196
<i>Of course, it had been
broken away from the boat.</i>

444
00:24:29,535 --> 00:24:32,049
<i>The shark got out and swam away,</i>

445
00:24:32,121 --> 00:24:35,580
but there were two other
sharks still in the area.

446
00:24:35,658 --> 00:24:39,686
And there was no way that
I could swim out of my cage

447
00:24:39,762 --> 00:24:40,854
and attach a rope.

448
00:24:40,929 --> 00:24:45,173
So what we did, we lowered
my cage down onto the bottom,

449
00:24:45,284 --> 00:24:48,493
and I put my feet through
the bottom of my cage,

450
00:24:48,570 --> 00:24:52,723
and picked my cage up, almost
like a lady pulls her skirt up,

451
00:24:52,825 --> 00:24:57,387
and walked the cage and myself
over the bottom about 50 feet

452
00:24:57,763 --> 00:25:01,290
to the other broken cage,
which was lying on the bottom,

453
00:25:01,400 --> 00:25:03,141
tied it to my cage,

454
00:25:03,218 --> 00:25:07,132
and then I signaled for them to
pull us both back to the surface.

455
00:25:17,316 --> 00:25:18,829
Then why don't we have one more drink

456
00:25:18,901 --> 00:25:21,165
and go down and cut that shark open?

457
00:25:22,121 --> 00:25:24,863
Martin?
Can you do that?

458
00:25:28,060 --> 00:25:31,246
I can do anything.
I'm the Chief of Police.

459
00:25:32,247 --> 00:25:36,081
Roy Scheider was interesting,
the story of how I cast him.

460
00:25:36,168 --> 00:25:39,445
Because here's a situation where
I was going after other actors.

461
00:25:39,521 --> 00:25:43,287
I went after a whole series of actors
before him, a lot of them unknowns.

462
00:25:43,358 --> 00:25:47,022
People that no one had
ever heard of before,

463
00:25:47,096 --> 00:25:49,076
but I was familiar with,
from seeing Serpico.

464
00:25:49,181 --> 00:25:51,980
There was an actor in Serpico
I kind of liked,

465
00:25:52,084 --> 00:25:55,395
and another actor on an
off-Broadway play I had just seen.

466
00:25:55,471 --> 00:25:59,567
But the studio and Zanuck and Brown
were urging me to get a name in this part.

467
00:25:59,641 --> 00:26:02,884
I was having trouble
finding a name that I liked,

468
00:26:02,995 --> 00:26:04,463
and who would do it.

469
00:26:04,546 --> 00:26:06,731
I remember I was at a party one night…

470
00:26:06,832 --> 00:26:11,315
And my agent brought me over
to be introduced to him.

471
00:26:11,386 --> 00:26:15,072
He was having a conversation with
a writer named Tracy Keenan Wynn.

472
00:26:15,657 --> 00:26:17,489
As I approached,

473
00:26:17,559 --> 00:26:19,744
I heard a conversation that
went something like this…

474
00:26:19,845 --> 00:26:24,339
"We're going to have to have this
giant shark come out of the water

475
00:26:24,450 --> 00:26:28,216
"and land on a boat
and crack the boat in half."

476
00:26:28,854 --> 00:26:33,064
And then I was introduced
to him and he said hello.

477
00:26:33,142 --> 00:26:34,655
He was very polite, nice, pleasant.

478
00:26:34,760 --> 00:26:38,754
Then, as I was walking away, they
picked up this conversation again.

479
00:26:38,864 --> 00:26:41,242
I remember saying to my
agent as we walked away,

480
00:26:41,316 --> 00:26:44,616
"Those guys, they gotta be kidding.

481
00:26:44,686 --> 00:26:48,736
"A giant shark that cracks a boat
in half?" I thought they were loony.

482
00:26:48,841 --> 00:26:50,718
I told him the entire story.

483
00:26:50,793 --> 00:26:52,522
At the end of the story he said,

484
00:26:52,594 --> 00:26:56,576
"Wow, that's a great story.
What about me?"

485
00:26:57,216 --> 00:27:01,119
I looked at Roy and I said, "Yeah,
you know, you'd be a great Chief Brody."

486
00:27:01,220 --> 00:27:03,530
<i>'Cause</i> I <i>had</i> loved <i>Roy from
The French Connection,</i>

487
00:27:03,605 --> 00:27:06,734
where he played Gene Hackman's partner.

488
00:27:06,809 --> 00:27:09,050
And that's how that came about.

489
00:27:09,695 --> 00:27:12,278
Could you tell me how I
could find Chief Brody?

490
00:27:12,347 --> 00:27:13,542
Who are you?

491
00:27:13,615 --> 00:27:15,856
Matt Hooper. I'm from
the Oceanographic Institute.

492
00:27:15,968 --> 00:27:18,482
Richard Dreyfuss wasn't
my first choice either.

493
00:27:18,554 --> 00:27:21,216
I went to Jon Voight first,
and he said no.

494
00:27:21,290 --> 00:27:23,850
I think I'd interviewed Timothy Bottoms.

495
00:27:23,926 --> 00:27:25,701
I interviewed a number of actors.

496
00:27:25,811 --> 00:27:27,711
Perhaps Jeff Bridges.

497
00:27:27,813 --> 00:27:30,180
I was a big fan of the entire
cast from <i>Last Picture</i> Show.

498
00:27:30,632 --> 00:27:34,296
I remember saying if I could
just get every member of the cast

499
00:27:34,369 --> 00:27:37,236
to say no to me to play
the Hooper character,

500
00:27:37,306 --> 00:27:40,685
at least I will have gone to one
of my favorite movies of all time,

501
00:27:40,776 --> 00:27:43,211
to have gone out after that group.

502
00:27:43,295 --> 00:27:45,354
So I think Bridges and Bottoms,

503
00:27:45,464 --> 00:27:46,898
and I think we got turned down,

504
00:27:46,999 --> 00:27:48,899
or there were unavailability problems.

505
00:27:49,001 --> 00:27:50,617
In the movies these things happen.

506
00:27:50,686 --> 00:27:52,427
People want to do it and they can't

507
00:27:52,538 --> 00:27:55,052
because they're booked
into something else.

508
00:27:56,792 --> 00:27:58,658
I remember Dreyfuss…

509
00:28:00,128 --> 00:28:03,371
I cast Dreyfuss because
I loved American Graffiti,

510
00:28:03,482 --> 00:28:04,699
and I had seen him in that.

511
00:28:04,766 --> 00:28:07,918
And George Lucas was
the person who said to me,

512
00:28:08,020 --> 00:28:11,229
"Why don't you cast Ricky
Dreyfuss? He'd be great."

513
00:28:11,673 --> 00:28:14,290
He told me this movie
that he wanted to make,

514
00:28:14,393 --> 00:28:16,919
and it was really a shocker.

515
00:28:17,029 --> 00:28:19,555
Even as he was telling it to me as a tale,

516
00:28:19,665 --> 00:28:23,465
it was a great, exciting story.

517
00:28:23,569 --> 00:28:27,972
These three guys alone on the boat,
and the shark attacking the boat and…

518
00:28:30,058 --> 00:28:32,937
At the end he said, "You
want to make this film?"

519
00:28:33,045 --> 00:28:34,888
And I said, “No."

520
00:28:34,980 --> 00:28:37,745
And he said, "Why not?"

521
00:28:37,833 --> 00:28:42,361
And I said, "This sounds like
it's going to be a great movie.

522
00:28:42,521 --> 00:28:44,785
"I'd rather watch this movie than shoot it

523
00:28:44,890 --> 00:28:47,882
"because it's going to be
a bitch to shoot."

524
00:28:48,527 --> 00:28:52,521
And I said… And he was surprised.

525
00:28:52,631 --> 00:28:57,592
I said, "I just wouldn't do well under
these circumstances," so I said no.

526
00:28:59,271 --> 00:29:03,606
Then a few months later, I went to see
the opening of a film I'd done in Canada.

527
00:29:05,177 --> 00:29:08,613
<i>It was the premiere of a film</i> called
<i>The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz.</i>

528
00:29:08,714 --> 00:29:12,298
And I saw myself,
really for the first time

529
00:29:13,018 --> 00:29:17,546
in the lead in a movie,
with my face 15 feet high,

530
00:29:18,190 --> 00:29:21,990
on screen for 90 minutes,
and I had a heart attack.

531
00:29:22,094 --> 00:29:25,746
I had a total nervous
collapse. I thought I was awful.

532
00:29:26,365 --> 00:29:29,949
I figured that I'd better
get a job really soon.

533
00:29:30,585 --> 00:29:32,053
So I called Steven.

534
00:29:32,788 --> 00:29:36,270
I said, "If you still want to
offer me that job, I'll take it."

535
00:29:36,842 --> 00:29:38,469
And he said yes.

536
00:29:39,111 --> 00:29:41,102
So, in essence,

537
00:29:41,747 --> 00:29:45,058
I came crawling to Martha's
Vineyard for the part.

538
00:29:47,135 --> 00:29:49,376
I don't want no volunteers.
I don't want no mates.

539
00:29:49,488 --> 00:29:52,219
There's too many captains on this island.

540
00:29:52,958 --> 00:29:55,393
$10,000 for me, by myself.

541
00:29:56,128 --> 00:30:00,907
For that you get the head,
the tail, the whole damn thing.

542
00:30:01,616 --> 00:30:04,176
My first choice to play Quint
was Lee Marvin.

543
00:30:04,987 --> 00:30:08,355
I wanted to go for
Lee Marvin to play Quint,

544
00:30:08,440 --> 00:30:10,772
but Lee Marvin wasn't interested.

545
00:30:12,611 --> 00:30:16,343
I think what I heard was, he
wanted to go fishing for real.

546
00:30:17,049 --> 00:30:20,462
He took his fishing seriously,
and didn't want to go fishing

547
00:30:20,535 --> 00:30:23,880
from a movie boat with cameras.

548
00:30:23,989 --> 00:30:25,787
That wasn't his idea of a vacation.

549
00:30:25,891 --> 00:30:29,452
It turned out not to be anybody's
idea of a vacation, making Jaws.

550
00:30:29,795 --> 00:30:32,526
My second choice was Sterling Hayden,

551
00:30:33,165 --> 00:30:37,375
who I thought would make an amazing Quint.

552
00:30:38,820 --> 00:30:41,585
He had an Ahab quality about him,

553
00:30:41,656 --> 00:30:45,502
and he had actually clone a movie
years ago, where he played a whaler

554
00:30:45,594 --> 00:30:47,642
with a harpoon that he
carried around with him.

555
00:30:47,746 --> 00:30:49,441
A very imposing character.

556
00:30:49,548 --> 00:30:50,879
I was a big fan of his,

557
00:30:50,966 --> 00:30:52,980
<i>certainly from Dr. Strange love</i>

558
00:30:53,085 --> 00:30:55,861
and, you know, the
two Kubrick films he did.

559
00:30:57,239 --> 00:30:59,515
And, as it turned out,
he couldn't do it either.

560
00:30:59,608 --> 00:31:02,726
I forgot actually what the
reason was he couldn't do it.

561
00:31:03,562 --> 00:31:07,362
And there were other actors
who wanted to play Quint,

562
00:31:07,466 --> 00:31:11,300
and then Dick Zanuck and David
Brown suggested Robert Shaw.

563
00:31:11,403 --> 00:31:15,636
It was their idea, because they had just
worked with Robert Shaw in The Sting,

564
00:31:15,741 --> 00:31:18,210
which they produced, and loved him.

565
00:31:18,894 --> 00:31:23,843
I'd screened two movies I'd already
seen of Shaw's, just to refresh my memory.

566
00:31:25,851 --> 00:31:28,320
<i>One oi them, of course,
was A Man for All Seasons.</i>

567
00:31:28,420 --> 00:31:30,582
He was spectacular in that.

568
00:31:31,239 --> 00:31:35,005
Based on that and, of course,
From <i>Russia with</i> Love…

569
00:31:35,761 --> 00:31:37,490
That great fight scene

570
00:31:37,596 --> 00:31:41,499
where he played the
nemesis of 007 in the train.

571
00:31:42,501 --> 00:31:45,482
I said, "Wow, I wish I had
thought of it. It's a great idea.“

572
00:31:45,554 --> 00:31:48,080
So he, fortunately, said yes.

573
00:31:48,173 --> 00:31:52,189
Robert was one of the most
powerful people I've ever met.

574
00:31:54,563 --> 00:31:56,406
Incredibly intense.

575
00:31:56,515 --> 00:31:59,928
I mean, it was something
that radiated out of him.

576
00:32:01,086 --> 00:32:04,545
He was a remarkably
gifted actor and writer.

577
00:32:05,190 --> 00:32:07,625
He was also, unfortunately,

578
00:32:07,742 --> 00:32:10,791
the most extraordinarily
competitive person.

579
00:32:11,213 --> 00:32:12,942
Unnecessarily competitive.

580
00:32:13,682 --> 00:32:16,515
<i>I think that probably, if anything,</i>

581
00:32:16,585 --> 00:32:18,804
<i>that was his flaw.</i>

582
00:32:19,321 --> 00:32:21,267
You got city hands,
Mr. Hooper.

583
00:32:21,373 --> 00:32:22,636
You been counting money all your life.

584
00:32:22,741 --> 00:32:24,709
All right, all right.
Hey, I don't need this.

585
00:32:24,810 --> 00:32:27,609
I don't need this working-class-hero crap.

586
00:32:27,696 --> 00:32:31,178
You're not going to do this
aboard the ship are you, Mr. Quint?

587
00:32:31,867 --> 00:32:36,555
Michael, did you hear your
father? Out of the water now!

588
00:32:36,605 --> 00:32:37,605
Now!

589
00:32:37,823 --> 00:32:41,726
The first person I cast for the
movie, in fact, was Lorraine,

590
00:32:41,827 --> 00:32:44,558
who I'd loved in a TV
movie I'd seen her do

591
00:32:44,663 --> 00:32:46,461
<i>called The Marcus-Nelson Murders,</i>

592
00:32:46,565 --> 00:32:48,249
starring Telly Savalas and herself,

593
00:32:48,316 --> 00:32:49,977
I believe, as Telly's in that.

594
00:32:50,051 --> 00:32:52,395
I thought she was a very natural actress,

595
00:32:52,504 --> 00:32:54,984
almost improvisational in her style.

596
00:32:55,056 --> 00:32:56,615
She brought a realism to the movie,

597
00:32:56,691 --> 00:32:59,103
and to that family, which I had wanted.

598
00:32:59,211 --> 00:33:01,942
Ellen is very clear to me
and always has been.

599
00:33:02,047 --> 00:33:04,732
You say Roy Scheider in his character

600
00:33:04,799 --> 00:33:06,733
feels guilt because of the children.

601
00:33:07,152 --> 00:33:09,211
I'm a mother, I'm a wife, and I'm Jewish.

602
00:33:09,321 --> 00:33:12,951
What could be clearer to me than
how to make somebody feel guilty?

603
00:33:13,058 --> 00:33:16,323
This is something that I do in
my sleep. It's what I've trained for.

604
00:33:16,428 --> 00:33:18,863
And I have two sons,
just like Ellen Brody.

605
00:33:18,964 --> 00:33:22,264
The suggestion that I made
to Steven at the time was

606
00:33:23,635 --> 00:33:26,548
to try to develop the script,

607
00:33:26,638 --> 00:33:30,654
so it had the same kind of
linear simplicity that Duel had.

608
00:33:31,243 --> 00:33:35,271
I thought that was
a reasonably good prototype

609
00:33:35,347 --> 00:33:37,975
to follow.

610
00:33:38,767 --> 00:33:41,782
And I remember some time later,

611
00:33:41,887 --> 00:33:46,302
my wife was upset with me…

612
00:33:46,374 --> 00:33:47,967
I put upset in quotes.

613
00:33:48,043 --> 00:33:51,525
Because a lot of the stuff that
we took out had to do with affairs

614
00:33:51,630 --> 00:33:53,314
that this particular character,

615
00:33:53,415 --> 00:33:55,110
as I recalled, had in the book.

616
00:33:55,217 --> 00:33:57,515
Of course I was upset about it,

617
00:33:57,586 --> 00:33:59,930
but I was very happy to be cast.

618
00:34:00,488 --> 00:34:03,901
Martin, it's all psychological.

619
00:34:04,009 --> 00:34:08,003
You yell, "Barracuda!" and
everybody says, "Huh? What?"

620
00:34:09,648 --> 00:34:12,162
You yell, "Shark!"…

621
00:34:12,234 --> 00:34:15,431
we've got a panic on our
hands on the Fourth of July.

622
00:34:15,554 --> 00:34:18,000
Murray Hamilton I've been a fan of,

623
00:34:18,073 --> 00:34:20,485
from The <i>FBI</i> Story with James Stewart

624
00:34:20,926 --> 00:34:24,556
to The Graduate and that great
scene, you know, with Dustin Hoffman,

625
00:34:24,663 --> 00:34:27,712
where he tells Dustin to go
off and sow some wild oats.

626
00:34:27,933 --> 00:34:29,617
I just always wanted to work with him.

627
00:34:29,701 --> 00:34:33,729
I was a big fan of his, and saw
him instantly as the mayor of Amity.

628
00:34:33,822 --> 00:34:36,871
So, I didn't have to
go through nine actors.

629
00:34:36,975 --> 00:34:39,034
He was the first choice for that part,

630
00:34:39,144 --> 00:34:40,657
and I was lucky enough to get him.

631
00:34:40,729 --> 00:34:42,561
I have to talk
to Mrs. Kintner.

632
00:34:42,631 --> 00:34:44,213
Because this is turning into a contest.

633
00:34:44,316 --> 00:34:47,399
It's not just the Gazette. She's
advertising in out-of-town papers.

634
00:34:47,469 --> 00:34:50,200
People all over New England
are going to know about it.

635
00:34:50,272 --> 00:34:52,570
<i>The most painful
thing I've ever done as a writer</i>

636
00:34:52,641 --> 00:34:56,202
is to take my part <i>as</i> an actor
and make it smaller and smaller,

637
00:34:56,328 --> 00:34:58,126
until it was almost gone.

638
00:34:58,213 --> 00:34:59,863
Even though I had good billing,

639
00:34:59,965 --> 00:35:03,811
I didn't follow through on screen

640
00:35:03,918 --> 00:35:06,797
with the amount of screen time
I would have liked as an actor.

641
00:35:06,905 --> 00:35:11,365
But it was better for the script that
my character not be there so much.

642
00:35:11,977 --> 00:35:15,777
Amity Island has long been
known for its clean air, clear water

643
00:35:15,864 --> 00:35:17,980
and beautiful white-sand beaches.

644
00:35:18,083 --> 00:35:19,983
But in recent days

645
00:35:20,085 --> 00:35:21,712
a cloud has appeared on the horizon

646
00:35:21,820 --> 00:35:23,504
of this beautiful resort community.

647
00:35:23,571 --> 00:35:26,188
A cloud in the shape of a killer shark.

648
00:35:26,291 --> 00:35:30,137
One of David Brown's geniuses was
to realize he could play upon the egos

649
00:35:30,211 --> 00:35:32,043
of writers, actors and other people

650
00:35:32,147 --> 00:35:33,797
who are not in the movie business

651
00:35:33,882 --> 00:35:37,091
by convincing us that only
by our appearing in the film

652
00:35:37,202 --> 00:35:39,534
could the film achieve its true greatness.

653
00:35:39,638 --> 00:35:42,630
So he came to me and said
would I consider, possibly

654
00:35:42,741 --> 00:35:45,790
as a favor to him, being in this movie?

655
00:35:45,860 --> 00:35:49,888
Well, to a person who's done television
for four years to be in a feature film?

656
00:35:50,015 --> 00:35:53,633
This was not exactly a request

657
00:35:53,702 --> 00:35:55,477
that I found it difficult to accept.

658
00:35:55,587 --> 00:35:57,487
So I said, "Sure!"
This was pure ego.

659
00:35:57,589 --> 00:35:58,704
Why not be in a feature film?

660
00:35:58,790 --> 00:36:01,168
It was no stretch for me.
It was no risk for him

661
00:36:01,242 --> 00:36:04,177
because I was a television
interviewer professionally, anyway.

662
00:36:04,245 --> 00:36:06,395
So I could do very little wrong.

663
00:36:07,082 --> 00:36:10,200
He wasn't asking me
to play an emotional scene.

664
00:36:10,285 --> 00:36:14,028
I was doing what I did for a
living, so it worked out very well.

665
00:36:14,873 --> 00:36:18,184
If there was a secondary
purpose to his request,

666
00:36:18,293 --> 00:36:20,944
and David is so wonderfully
gracious that you never know

667
00:36:21,046 --> 00:36:24,630
whether he's just being nice to
you or there's something underneath,

668
00:36:24,733 --> 00:36:28,146
it would have been that because
of the publicity surrounding the book

669
00:36:28,253 --> 00:36:32,417
and surrounding the movie,
it couldn't hurt to have me

670
00:36:33,108 --> 00:36:35,736
in the movie, in some category or other.

671
00:36:35,844 --> 00:36:38,962
In Amity Island, this is Alan Cray.

672
00:36:39,064 --> 00:36:40,941
I want to try that end again.

673
00:36:41,316 --> 00:36:42,363
Okay?

674
00:36:43,802 --> 00:36:47,215
And there you have it. Two different
opinions by two men of goodwill.

675
00:36:47,288 --> 00:36:51,168
But here in Amity, it seems it's
the public that's making up its mind.

676
00:36:51,276 --> 00:36:54,018
On Amity Island, this is Alan Cray.

677
00:36:55,196 --> 00:36:56,664
All right, Murray, that'll do it.

678
00:36:56,765 --> 00:36:58,073
Cut!

679
00:36:58,133 --> 00:36:59,225
Save if!

680
00:36:59,968 --> 00:37:03,871
When it came down to
where we would shoot this film,

681
00:37:03,938 --> 00:37:08,603
we sent Joe Alves, our
production designer, out with a team

682
00:37:09,043 --> 00:37:13,412
to give us some ideas and
some photographs and pictures of

683
00:37:14,249 --> 00:37:17,150
where this town

684
00:37:18,870 --> 00:37:22,716
should be shot, including Jamaica.

685
00:37:22,791 --> 00:37:26,352
We thought of Jamaica primarily
because of the clarity of the water.

686
00:37:26,428 --> 00:37:31,013
We could do underwater
work down there, do it all there.

687
00:37:31,116 --> 00:37:35,804
And one of the places, obviously,
that they went, among others,

688
00:37:35,954 --> 00:37:38,150
was the island of Martha's Vineyard.

689
00:37:38,423 --> 00:37:41,575
Which, believe it or not,
had never been photographed

690
00:37:41,643 --> 00:37:43,270
by a feature film before.

691
00:37:43,344 --> 00:37:48,123
They had very strict rules
and regulations there,

692
00:37:48,716 --> 00:37:51,959
and had always kept movie companies in.

693
00:37:52,070 --> 00:37:56,337
So it really was a question
of talking them into letting,

694
00:37:56,624 --> 00:37:58,649
at the height of their season,

695
00:37:58,726 --> 00:38:00,820
letting a big movie company come in there.

696
00:38:00,929 --> 00:38:05,810
Martha's Vineyard did present
the problem that this pristine place,

697
00:38:06,151 --> 00:38:09,735
unchanged since the 18th century,

698
00:38:10,355 --> 00:38:13,666
didn't particularly care
for a movie invasion.

699
00:38:13,741 --> 00:38:16,836
They didn't like to see
an artificial shark

700
00:38:17,045 --> 00:38:20,845
parked in a channel
where their homes faced it.

701
00:38:20,949 --> 00:38:24,852
And the only set that we built,

702
00:38:24,936 --> 00:38:27,416
<i>which was Quint's shack,</i>

703
00:38:27,489 --> 00:38:30,618
<i>we had to post a bond
with the town authorities</i>

704
00:38:30,692 --> 00:38:34,344
<i>that everything would be
replaced exactly the way it was.</i>

705
00:38:34,429 --> 00:38:36,329
The billboard in the picture…

706
00:38:36,397 --> 00:38:40,015
They put up a billboard
and some kids have come along

707
00:38:40,118 --> 00:38:44,646
<i>and made a prank out of it, painted it
with the shark and "Help" and so forth.</i>

708
00:38:44,756 --> 00:38:49,273
We had to put up that billboard
one morning, shoot the scene,

709
00:38:49,344 --> 00:38:52,507
and take it down at the end of the day.

710
00:38:53,598 --> 00:38:55,908
That was the only way we could shoot that.

711
00:38:55,984 --> 00:38:58,453
There could be nothing done…

712
00:38:58,520 --> 00:39:01,512
We could do nothing to alter the landscape

713
00:39:01,606 --> 00:39:05,554
or the beautiful harmony
that existed on the island.

714
00:39:05,627 --> 00:39:07,721
The real attraction of Martha's Vineyard,

715
00:39:07,795 --> 00:39:09,524
you couldn't see with the naked eye.

716
00:39:09,614 --> 00:39:12,481
It was the only place on the East Coast

717
00:39:12,584 --> 00:39:14,461
where I could go 12 miles out to sea

718
00:39:14,802 --> 00:39:19,740
and still have a sandy bottom only
30 feet below the surface of the water,

719
00:39:19,807 --> 00:39:21,571
where we could put the shark sled

720
00:39:21,643 --> 00:39:24,544
and the mechanical shark could function.

721
00:39:24,812 --> 00:39:29,227
So Martha's Vineyard was chosen
less because it was a picturesque village.

722
00:39:29,334 --> 00:39:31,428
I could've shot this movie in Sag Harbor

723
00:39:31,536 --> 00:39:33,846
or Montauk or a number of places.

724
00:39:33,922 --> 00:39:37,859
It was because of that sandy
bottom 12 miles offshore.

725
00:39:37,926 --> 00:39:41,294
It was very important that no matter
what direction my cameras turned,

726
00:39:41,362 --> 00:39:42,921
I didn't want to see land.

727
00:39:43,014 --> 00:39:44,197
I felt…

728
00:39:44,299 --> 00:39:47,701
My fear was, the minute the
audience saw land, they'd say,

729
00:39:47,769 --> 00:39:49,601
"This is getting pretty intense out here.

730
00:39:49,671 --> 00:39:53,050
"Just turn the boat around and go
toward that land that we keep seeing."

731
00:39:53,141 --> 00:39:55,132
I wanted the audience
to feel very cut off,

732
00:39:55,209 --> 00:39:57,109
like they couldn't run back to shore,

733
00:39:57,211 --> 00:39:58,940
'cause there was no shore to run back to.

734
00:39:59,197 --> 00:40:01,882
I was tipped off by somebody on the crew…

735
00:40:01,950 --> 00:40:04,726
We were still here at the Universal lot.

736
00:40:04,836 --> 00:40:06,418
That Steven was going to come in,

737
00:40:06,487 --> 00:40:10,355
and he was really thinking
about withdrawing

738
00:40:10,425 --> 00:40:13,326
'cause he was very concerned
about the way things were going.

739
00:40:13,394 --> 00:40:16,853
The shark wasn't working.
It seemed hopeless.

740
00:40:16,965 --> 00:40:20,014
The script was far from perfect.

741
00:40:21,235 --> 00:40:23,545
And a few weeks before, he had

742
00:40:23,655 --> 00:40:25,805
had some T-shirts made up

743
00:40:25,873 --> 00:40:29,867
with a big shark on it saying "JAWS."

744
00:40:29,978 --> 00:40:32,697
And so

745
00:40:32,780 --> 00:40:36,592
knowing what he was
coming in to talk to me about,

746
00:40:37,719 --> 00:40:39,130
I put on a T-shirt.

747
00:40:39,237 --> 00:40:44,084
I put on this T-shirt and was sitting
behind my desk when he came in.

748
00:40:44,158 --> 00:40:46,502
And just seeing me there, I think,

749
00:40:46,611 --> 00:40:48,887
in front of the desk with this T-shirt…

750
00:40:48,997 --> 00:40:50,715
And I was saying, "This is the greatest.

751
00:40:50,798 --> 00:40:52,880
"We're going to kill them with this.

752
00:40:52,984 --> 00:40:55,203
"It's great, and you're
going to be great for it."

753
00:40:55,269 --> 00:40:59,570
It kind of lifted him back into it.

754
00:40:59,691 --> 00:41:03,002
Steven is the most
enthusiastic man I've ever met,

755
00:41:03,094 --> 00:41:05,358
and it brought back that enthusiasm.

756
00:41:06,998 --> 00:41:08,272
What's your name again?

757
00:41:08,366 --> 00:41:09,583
Chrissie.

758
00:41:10,268 --> 00:41:11,360
Where are we going?

759
00:41:11,436 --> 00:41:12,436
Swimming!

760
00:41:12,537 --> 00:41:15,416
<i>I started doing
stunt work, and I specialized in water.</i>

761
00:41:15,490 --> 00:41:18,141
<i>A lot of times when the
water stunts would come up,</i>

762
00:41:18,226 --> 00:41:20,558
<i>I got into doing the water stunts also.</i>

763
00:41:21,129 --> 00:41:24,190
<i>Steven Spielberg was a
little bit leery having me</i>

764
00:41:24,298 --> 00:41:26,812
<i>because I wasn't an actress per se.</i>

765
00:41:28,136 --> 00:41:29,604
After the first day of shooting…

766
00:41:29,671 --> 00:41:32,971
We did the beach scene the
first day, the party scene at night.

767
00:41:33,041 --> 00:41:35,339
We got along wonderful after that.

768
00:41:35,410 --> 00:41:37,469
Whatever I did, he liked.

769
00:41:37,578 --> 00:41:39,569
It was great. He was a
great person to work for.

770
00:41:47,205 --> 00:41:48,616
Come on in the water!

771
00:41:48,840 --> 00:41:52,219
I thought that what could really
be scary was not seeing the shark

772
00:41:52,326 --> 00:41:55,569
and just seeing the water, because
we all are familiar with the water.

773
00:41:55,680 --> 00:41:57,580
Very few of us have been
in the water with a shark,

774
00:41:57,682 --> 00:41:59,480
but we've all gone swimming.

775
00:41:59,584 --> 00:42:02,178
The idea of this girl going swimming,

776
00:42:02,270 --> 00:42:04,261
and the audience going swimming with her

777
00:42:04,338 --> 00:42:07,490
would have been too
extraordinary if, like a leviathan,

778
00:42:07,592 --> 00:42:09,219
the shark had come out of the water

779
00:42:09,327 --> 00:42:11,853
with its jaws agape, and come down on her.

780
00:42:11,963 --> 00:42:14,694
It would have been a
spectacular opening for the film,

781
00:42:14,799 --> 00:42:17,928
but there would have been
nothing primal about it.

782
00:42:18,036 --> 00:42:21,199
It would just have been a
monster moment that we've all seen.

783
00:42:21,289 --> 00:42:24,873
I really wanted to do it without
seeing the shark in that case.

784
00:42:24,976 --> 00:42:28,071
I wanted the violent,
jerking motions to just

785
00:42:28,179 --> 00:42:31,023
<i>start to trigger our
imaginations into either</i>

786
00:42:31,099 --> 00:42:34,581
<i>thinking about what's happening
below the surface of the waterline</i>

787
00:42:34,669 --> 00:42:37,445
<i>or blocking what was
happening below the surface.</i>

788
00:42:41,576 --> 00:42:44,352
The first jerk down Steven did.

789
00:42:44,912 --> 00:42:48,109
He had a cable that came
to the front of my stomach

790
00:42:48,199 --> 00:42:51,692
and went to an anchor that was
laying on the bottom of the ocean.

791
00:42:51,803 --> 00:42:54,636
Then he just sat, and
when he wanted that pulled,

792
00:42:54,739 --> 00:42:55,900
he just would pull.

793
00:42:56,074 --> 00:42:57,633
I could feel him pulling down,

794
00:42:57,742 --> 00:42:59,904
and I'd just throw my head back even more.

795
00:43:02,296 --> 00:43:05,482
They wanted to put me
on an electric winch,

796
00:43:05,566 --> 00:43:09,013
and I prefer not to use an electric winch

797
00:43:09,454 --> 00:43:13,448
because if any of the line
overrode and came to a stop,

798
00:43:13,558 --> 00:43:16,391
I might not know it and I
might not be able to get out of it.

799
00:43:16,494 --> 00:43:20,021
Being they're pulling me back and
forth in the water, I wanted more control.

800
00:43:20,131 --> 00:43:21,872
<i>So we used manpower.</i>

801
00:43:21,949 --> 00:43:25,442
<i>They put cutoff Levis on and
had cables running from me,</i>

802
00:43:25,520 --> 00:43:27,887
out to the side to two pilings,

803
00:43:27,955 --> 00:43:30,003
and then all the way in to the beach.

804
00:43:30,108 --> 00:43:33,408
What they would do is, we put
marks on the beach and the guys,

805
00:43:33,511 --> 00:43:35,570
we'd have five or six guys on each line,

806
00:43:35,680 --> 00:43:38,672
and they would run back
and forth from mark to mark.

807
00:43:38,783 --> 00:43:40,376
So I didn't have the hard work to do.

808
00:43:40,485 --> 00:43:42,647
I just sat there and got pulled around.

809
00:43:42,737 --> 00:43:45,206
The guys were running
back and forth on the beach.

810
00:43:45,273 --> 00:43:49,710
And that's what made my body
move back and forth in the frame.

811
00:43:49,894 --> 00:43:53,057
When I would feel my hips
getting pulled the opposite way,

812
00:43:53,164 --> 00:43:57,010
I'd just throw my arms out of
water very violently the opposite way.

813
00:43:57,168 --> 00:44:00,433
So, physically, I could make it
look more violent than what it was.

814
00:44:02,356 --> 00:44:04,165
It hurts!

815
00:44:06,727 --> 00:44:11,540
I went to a marine store
and bought a safety hook

816
00:44:11,632 --> 00:44:15,318
that you'd use on a sail,
on the halyard of a sail.

817
00:44:15,403 --> 00:44:18,202
I put it onto all the cables
that they hooked to me.

818
00:44:18,289 --> 00:44:20,053
So that, any time during this scene,

819
00:44:20,158 --> 00:44:21,887
if I got in trouble, if I got water,

820
00:44:21,993 --> 00:44:24,041
if I got hurt, God knows what happen,

821
00:44:24,111 --> 00:44:26,261
I could pull one of those strings,

822
00:44:26,364 --> 00:44:29,095
and I was free and clear
and could come to the surface.

823
00:44:29,200 --> 00:44:33,012
So it allowed me, if I got
in a spot, to free myself.

824
00:44:33,120 --> 00:44:36,317
How would anybody know if I
was hurt or I needed anything?

825
00:44:36,390 --> 00:44:38,324
I'm out there screaming like a fool.

826
00:44:40,745 --> 00:44:42,110
Oh, my God!

827
00:44:42,213 --> 00:44:45,205
In the scene where I
was pulled into the buoy,

828
00:44:45,483 --> 00:44:47,815
Steven said, "Let's
have you say something.

829
00:44:47,919 --> 00:44:50,081
"We'll have you say The Lord's Prayer.

830
00:44:50,188 --> 00:44:53,715
"Don't the Catholics say
something if they're going to die?

831
00:44:53,808 --> 00:44:56,869
"They say something they're
going to say in the confessional,

832
00:44:56,961 --> 00:44:59,931
"asking God to forgive you
for all your sins."

833
00:45:00,231 --> 00:45:03,667
Unfortunately, I hadn't been going
to church for the last few years,

834
00:45:03,768 --> 00:45:05,247
and I could not remember it.

835
00:45:05,336 --> 00:45:07,498
I swear there were eight Catholics on set,

836
00:45:07,605 --> 00:45:10,199
and between the eight of us
we couldn't come up with it.

837
00:45:10,308 --> 00:45:11,685
I felt very bad.

838
00:45:17,832 --> 00:45:19,982
Oh, God, help!

839
00:45:20,434 --> 00:45:22,698
Please help me!

840
00:45:23,221 --> 00:45:25,030
We looped the film.

841
00:45:25,106 --> 00:45:27,837
A lot of stuff we couldn't do
because of the noise made.

842
00:45:27,909 --> 00:45:30,423
So you go into a looping studio.

843
00:45:30,895 --> 00:45:33,796
The idea was, how are you going
to sound like you're in the water

844
00:45:33,898 --> 00:45:35,332
sitting in a studio?

845
00:45:35,433 --> 00:45:38,277
So we came up with the
idea of getting a baby bassinet

846
00:45:38,369 --> 00:45:39,586
and filling it with water.

847
00:45:39,654 --> 00:45:41,213
So I'm sitting on the sound stage,

848
00:45:41,289 --> 00:45:43,053
with the film up on the screen,

849
00:45:43,124 --> 00:45:45,343
on a stool with my little bassinet,

850
00:45:45,443 --> 00:45:47,275
and Richard Dreyfuss came in.

851
00:45:47,461 --> 00:45:50,806
I came to visit Steven or I
came to do my own looping.

852
00:45:50,915 --> 00:45:53,816
I'm not really sure now.
It was so long ago.

853
00:45:55,136 --> 00:45:59,619
I walked in and Steven had
this beautiful girl's blond head

854
00:45:59,740 --> 00:46:01,230
reared back like this,

855
00:46:01,309 --> 00:46:04,256
and he was pouring water
down her throat like this.

856
00:46:04,996 --> 00:46:08,114
And telling her to scream
her bloody lungs out.

857
00:46:09,100 --> 00:46:13,003
Which I thought was a rather
interesting way to spend the afternoon,

858
00:46:13,104 --> 00:46:15,801
but not particularly comfortable for her.

859
00:46:15,890 --> 00:46:18,109
But it does work for the movie.

860
00:46:18,209 --> 00:46:21,577
The reason they were doing it
was to make the appropriate sound.

861
00:46:21,679 --> 00:46:23,477
They couldn't do it any other way,

862
00:46:23,581 --> 00:46:26,016
so he just poured that
water down her throat.

863
00:46:30,972 --> 00:46:32,269
Oh, Jesus.

864
00:46:32,340 --> 00:46:34,650
The problem was,
they brought the hand to me

865
00:46:34,759 --> 00:46:37,854
and they said, "Here's
the dead girl's hand."

866
00:46:37,962 --> 00:46:41,592
I said, "Wow, it looks like
shiny plastic. It looks fake."

867
00:46:42,133 --> 00:46:45,228
They said, "After a
body's been decomposing

868
00:46:45,336 --> 00:46:48,647
"for a day on the sand,
with the sun coming down,

869
00:46:48,723 --> 00:46:50,191
"it takes on that look."

870
00:46:50,257 --> 00:46:52,771
I said, "You might be clinically right,

871
00:46:52,877 --> 00:46:55,676
"and a pathologist might look at that

872
00:46:55,780 --> 00:46:57,942
"and admire that moment in Jaws,

873
00:46:58,049 --> 00:47:00,950
"but to me, <i>as</i> an audience
member, it looks fake.

874
00:47:01,052 --> 00:47:02,463
"It looks like plastic."

875
00:47:02,636 --> 00:47:06,948
We tried putting powder on it
to get the reflective shine off.

876
00:47:07,058 --> 00:47:10,210
We couldn't do that.
So I said, "Well, screw it."

877
00:47:10,695 --> 00:47:14,142
I believe I turned to someone
and said, "Let me use your arm."

878
00:47:14,215 --> 00:47:16,058
Kind of like we do when we're kids,

879
00:47:16,167 --> 00:47:17,942
we bury our parents in the sand.

880
00:47:18,019 --> 00:47:19,635
I kind of buried her in the sand,

881
00:47:19,737 --> 00:47:21,535
and just had her hand sticking out.

882
00:47:21,639 --> 00:47:24,483
We made up part of the arm,
so right up here,

883
00:47:24,558 --> 00:47:28,176
it looked like it had been
bitten off, kind of a subtle way.

884
00:47:28,279 --> 00:47:29,974
Then there were these sand crabs that

885
00:47:30,081 --> 00:47:32,072
we collected and put all over the arm.

886
00:47:32,183 --> 00:47:34,447
They were kind of lethargic
in their movements.

887
00:47:34,552 --> 00:47:36,350
To this day, when I see <i>Jaws,</i>

888
00:47:36,454 --> 00:47:38,604
I always have this different vision

889
00:47:38,672 --> 00:47:42,119
of 10 times as many crabs
moving 10 times as fast,

890
00:47:42,510 --> 00:47:44,524
trying to feed on the arm.

891
00:47:44,612 --> 00:47:47,627
Later I was able to do that
in Temple <i>Of</i> Doom,

892
00:47:47,732 --> 00:47:51,293
when I was able to get the bugs
to do what the crabs couldn't do

893
00:47:51,402 --> 00:47:53,496
15 years earlier.

894
00:48:00,211 --> 00:48:04,773
The death of the Kintner boy, and
all the paranoia, tension and suspense

895
00:48:05,166 --> 00:48:08,466
leading up to the actual
attack when he's out on the raft,

896
00:48:08,536 --> 00:48:11,233
I, in my mind, wanted to do in one shot.

897
00:48:12,339 --> 00:48:15,491
In trying to figure out,
in a perfect world,

898
00:48:15,593 --> 00:48:18,961
how could I have done that
in one sustained shot,

899
00:48:19,063 --> 00:48:20,861
I came up with the idea

900
00:48:20,965 --> 00:48:23,866
to have bathers with
different-colored bathing suits

901
00:48:23,984 --> 00:48:26,214
walking in front of the camera

902
00:48:26,287 --> 00:48:28,506
<i>that would wipe off Roy Scheider.</i>

903
00:48:28,773 --> 00:48:30,571
<i>The same color in the reverse,</i>

904
00:48:30,658 --> 00:48:32,342
<i>moving in the other direction,</i>

905
00:48:32,443 --> 00:48:34,605
<i>would wipe on what he's looking at.</i>

906
00:48:34,712 --> 00:48:36,612
<i>Which, even though
it wouldn't be one shot,</i>

907
00:48:36,714 --> 00:48:39,513
<i>would give more of a seamless feeling</i>

908
00:48:40,301 --> 00:48:43,043
<i>and much more of a clear point of view</i>

909
00:48:43,154 --> 00:48:45,236
<i>that you knew who was looking at who.</i>

910
00:48:45,306 --> 00:48:48,685
All this must be from the
police chief's point of view.

911
00:48:48,793 --> 00:48:50,955
The scene's about him.
It's about his reaction.

912
00:48:51,045 --> 00:48:52,956
It's not about the
Kintner boy being killed.

913
00:48:53,047 --> 00:48:55,960
It's about the chief of
police, his fear of the water,

914
00:48:56,050 --> 00:48:58,735
his chief responsibility
to protect the public,

915
00:48:58,836 --> 00:49:00,895
his fear that there is a shark out there,

916
00:49:01,005 --> 00:49:02,439
and he knows it's out there,

917
00:49:02,540 --> 00:49:05,384
<i>and these people
are going swimming anyway.</i>

918
00:49:08,012 --> 00:49:10,060
Did you see that?

919
00:49:24,128 --> 00:49:25,175
Hello.

920
00:49:25,246 --> 00:49:27,658
Hello back, young fellow.
How are you?

921
00:49:27,932 --> 00:49:30,299
Craig Kings bury was a local
on Martha's Vineyard,

922
00:49:30,401 --> 00:49:32,028
and he was quite a character.

923
00:49:32,136 --> 00:49:34,400
He himself was a movie and a book.

924
00:49:36,090 --> 00:49:39,469
Had I not gotten Robert Shaw

925
00:49:39,577 --> 00:49:41,944
and had I met him in an open casting call,

926
00:49:42,046 --> 00:49:46,563
I might have come close to flirting
with the idea of using him to play Quint.

927
00:49:46,634 --> 00:49:50,616
Because he was the purest version

928
00:49:51,322 --> 00:49:53,905
of who, in my mind, Quint really was.

929
00:49:54,275 --> 00:49:56,573
When I met him, he came
up with this great dialogue.

930
00:49:56,644 --> 00:49:58,760
I kept increasing his part.

931
00:49:58,863 --> 00:50:01,639
Just by meeting him I said,
"I want you to be in my movie,

932
00:50:01,749 --> 00:50:03,490
"and you can make up your own dialogue."

933
00:50:03,601 --> 00:50:06,036
He made up the stuff when
he's in the boat and he says,

934
00:50:06,120 --> 00:50:08,669
"You're gonna wish your
mothers never met your fathers

935
00:50:08,756 --> 00:50:10,747
"when you start piling
