959
00:51:23,414 --> 00:51:27,214
The thing that really has lasted
through the years with Steven and me

960
00:51:27,318 --> 00:51:29,195
is a very private code.

961
00:51:30,371 --> 00:51:33,682
At the dinner table scene,
I improvised something

962
00:51:34,425 --> 00:51:36,302
about a Cousteau show I had seen.

963
00:51:36,377 --> 00:51:39,688
And years later, 20 years later,

964
00:51:39,797 --> 00:51:43,279
Sid and I were given an award
by the Wiesenthal Center,

965
00:51:43,484 --> 00:51:47,011
and Steven was the one who
presented it on their behalf.

966
00:51:47,438 --> 00:51:50,601
He talked about Sid and
all the things he's done,

967
00:51:51,008 --> 00:51:53,488
and presented his whatever,

968
00:51:53,611 --> 00:51:57,855
and then introduced me and told
about the things that I've been doing.

969
00:51:57,931 --> 00:52:02,391
Then, as he turned to me, he said,
"Lorraine, remember the sea otter?"

970
00:52:02,620 --> 00:52:03,815
Marker.

971
00:52:14,999 --> 00:52:18,196
Did you ever see the television special,

972
00:52:18,302 --> 00:52:19,929
the Cousteau special on sea otters?

973
00:52:20,037 --> 00:52:23,086
Sea otters, where the mother
was killed in front of the baby.

974
00:52:23,157 --> 00:52:24,989
The baby saw it with his eyes.

975
00:52:25,059 --> 00:52:26,800
You could see the tears
coming down his face.

976
00:52:26,894 --> 00:52:30,057
It was the most incredible thing
I have ever seen. It was terrible.

977
00:52:30,164 --> 00:52:33,259
Mikey wanted us to
adopt the sea otter. It was…

978
00:52:33,434 --> 00:52:37,678
I've never been this moved by
anything on television. It was really…

979
00:52:37,805 --> 00:52:39,330
It was special.

980
00:52:40,024 --> 00:52:41,321
So…

981
00:52:42,326 --> 00:52:46,536
You're going on the Aurora. You're
going to live there 18 months. Wow.

982
00:52:47,281 --> 00:52:49,648
It was disappointing to me
it wasn't in the movie.

983
00:52:49,717 --> 00:52:53,199
Not as disappointing as not having
a sex scene with Richard Dreyfuss,

984
00:52:53,287 --> 00:52:55,028
but it was disappointing.

985
00:53:02,463 --> 00:53:04,932
Shark! A shark!

986
00:53:08,152 --> 00:53:10,587
<i>I was going to be a victim in the estuary.</i>

987
00:53:10,688 --> 00:53:13,157
<i>I'm in a little rowboat.</i>

988
00:53:13,374 --> 00:53:16,583
The way they shot it the first time,

989
00:53:16,694 --> 00:53:20,210
I'm in the shark's mouth
with a blood pack in my mouth.

990
00:53:20,280 --> 00:53:24,524
I'm going on top of water,
underwater, spitting blood out,

991
00:53:24,635 --> 00:53:26,535
and I'm trying to make a lot of movement,

992
00:53:26,637 --> 00:53:29,868
but it was very awkward
the way this seat was.

993
00:53:29,957 --> 00:53:33,234
I was trying to make a lot of
movement like I was in the shark's mouth.

994
00:53:33,327 --> 00:53:34,658
Going underwater, top of water.

995
00:53:34,762 --> 00:53:36,287
Then I see

996
00:53:37,848 --> 00:53:40,397
Roy's son staring at me.

997
00:53:40,484 --> 00:53:43,715
As a last-ditch effort, the shark
is heading right towards him.

998
00:53:43,821 --> 00:53:46,973
I just make a move to
grab him, and I let him just…

999
00:53:47,040 --> 00:53:48,974
I just touched him and let him go,

1000
00:53:49,042 --> 00:53:50,976
and then I go underwater and disappear.

1001
00:53:51,245 --> 00:53:53,407
What happened in that scene is,

1002
00:53:53,514 --> 00:53:56,142
it was so violent and so horrendous

1003
00:53:56,316 --> 00:54:00,583
<i>that they couldn't use it. It
was just too violent, period.</i>

1004
00:54:03,207 --> 00:54:06,006
<i>I was in this bucket seat,
strapped into it,</i>

1005
00:54:06,110 --> 00:54:08,522
<i>and the shark fin was behind me on a sled.</i>

1006
00:54:08,629 --> 00:54:12,429
<i>I had the kid in my arms, and I
was gonna take him underwater.</i>

1007
00:54:12,533 --> 00:54:16,060
<i>Then I let him go, and
the sled went underwater.</i>

1008
00:54:20,224 --> 00:54:22,738
Teddy Grossman is in
the jaws of the shark.

1009
00:54:22,810 --> 00:54:24,073
The shark's underwater.

1010
00:54:24,178 --> 00:54:27,523
And Teddy, like the maidenhead on a ship,

1011
00:54:28,081 --> 00:54:31,164
is traveling toward
this kid, vomiting blood.

1012
00:54:31,285 --> 00:54:34,346
That's much more horrible
than what I had done,

1013
00:54:34,455 --> 00:54:37,390
you know, in the first third of <i>Jaws</i>.

1014
00:54:37,541 --> 00:54:39,851
I just didn't like it.
It was too bloody.

1015
00:54:39,927 --> 00:54:41,986
I thought it was in
bad taste, so I cut it out.

1016
00:54:42,996 --> 00:54:46,455
Come on, Chief. This
isn't no Boy Scout picnic.

1017
00:54:46,917 --> 00:54:49,033
See you got your rubbers.

1018
00:54:49,102 --> 00:54:52,811
I asked Robert to
give Lorraine a hard time

1019
00:54:53,157 --> 00:54:54,716
inside the scene,

1020
00:54:55,042 --> 00:54:58,478
'cause he's really sort of
putting down Chief Brody.

1021
00:54:58,645 --> 00:55:01,012
He thinks Chief Brady's a sissy.

1022
00:55:01,114 --> 00:55:04,163
He's putting down the fact
he's all in rubber.

1023
00:55:04,268 --> 00:55:07,363
He says, "Are you glad you
brought your rubbers, Chief?"

1024
00:55:07,471 --> 00:55:10,202
And he's always doing this to everybody,

1025
00:55:10,591 --> 00:55:13,492
to Brady's character,
to Brody and to Hooper.

1026
00:55:14,595 --> 00:55:18,054
And so I asked him to chide Lorraine,

1027
00:55:18,131 --> 00:55:20,156
and in the middle of the scene

1028
00:55:20,234 --> 00:55:22,396
he made up this little poem that went,

1029
00:55:22,870 --> 00:55:27,023
"There was a woman named Mary
Who lost her virginity

1030
00:55:28,442 --> 00:55:30,274
"Not a bad record for this vicinity"

1031
00:55:30,344 --> 00:55:31,869
Whatever it was, when it was over,

1032
00:55:31,962 --> 00:55:33,771
I said, "You gotta help me clear this.

1033
00:55:33,881 --> 00:55:35,315
"If that's from a song,

1034
00:55:35,415 --> 00:55:38,134
"we just can't use that
without paying for the rights."

1035
00:55:38,235 --> 00:55:42,399
He said, "I don't think we'll be sued.
I got it from a tombstone in Ireland."

1036
00:55:42,506 --> 00:55:45,089
<i>That's where he found that little ditty.</i>

1037
00:55:45,242 --> 00:55:49,827
"Here lies the body of Mary
Lee Died at the age of 103

1038
00:55:49,897 --> 00:55:52,525
"For 15 years she kept her virginity

1039
00:55:52,633 --> 00:55:54,852
"Not a bad record for this vicinity"

1040
00:55:57,070 --> 00:56:01,018
If they don't like you
going out, they'll love you coming in.

1041
00:56:07,714 --> 00:56:10,991
<i>For</i> Jaws, <i>I
wanted the color red to be the blood</i>

1042
00:56:11,268 --> 00:56:14,636
<i>and not to be a bandana
around someone's neck</i>

1043
00:56:14,821 --> 00:56:18,815
<i>or a plaid over shirt
or the letters on a boat.</i>

1044
00:56:19,092 --> 00:56:21,322
The only red I wanted
in the movie was blood.

1045
00:56:21,395 --> 00:56:24,456
I told the production designer,
Joe Alves, at the very beginning,

1046
00:56:24,565 --> 00:56:26,363
"When you're designing the picture

1047
00:56:26,466 --> 00:56:29,185
"and finding your colors, don't find red.

1048
00:56:29,286 --> 00:56:31,562
"Just allow red to be the blood."

1049
00:56:32,139 --> 00:56:34,301
And, in a sense, I think we stuck to that.

1050
00:56:34,374 --> 00:56:36,183
I think that's what happened.

1051
00:56:36,293 --> 00:56:40,105
We did have red wine,
but it's a bit symbolic.

1052
00:56:45,102 --> 00:56:46,581
Keep that chum line going, Chief.

1053
00:56:46,670 --> 00:56:48,365
We got five good miles on it.

1054
00:56:48,472 --> 00:56:50,736
<i>When the shooting started at sea,</i>

1055
00:56:50,841 --> 00:56:52,957
<i>the production got a lot more difficult.</i>

1056
00:56:53,393 --> 00:56:56,670
That's when they started
worrying about wind and weather,

1057
00:56:56,763 --> 00:56:58,857
when they could spend a day on the ocean

1058
00:56:58,966 --> 00:57:01,446
and get six seconds of usable film

1059
00:57:01,535 --> 00:57:03,082
because of boats on the horizon,

1060
00:57:03,170 --> 00:57:04,752
because of malfunctioning shark.

1061
00:57:04,855 --> 00:57:07,904
The problems of shooting
at sea are enormous

1062
00:57:07,975 --> 00:57:12,242
because the wind, the waves,
everything is moving

1063
00:57:12,779 --> 00:57:17,148
and nothing stays the same
for more than 50, 60 seconds.

1064
00:57:17,417 --> 00:57:20,296
I would set up a shot and
I'd get my camera all set.

1065
00:57:20,404 --> 00:57:22,714
Suddenly the electrical barge
would start drifting,

1066
00:57:22,789 --> 00:57:24,302
the tide would be moving this way,

1067
00:57:24,408 --> 00:57:26,718
and the camera barge
would start drifting this way,

1068
00:57:26,793 --> 00:57:29,421
and the Orca would start
moving around on its two anchors.

1069
00:57:29,529 --> 00:57:31,714
Before you knew it,
we were all out of position.

1070
00:57:31,798 --> 00:57:34,779
It took another hour and a half
to re-anchor and get set again.

1071
00:57:34,885 --> 00:57:38,048
Just when we got set, sailboats
from a regatta would come in.

1072
00:57:38,155 --> 00:57:40,806
You're shooting
towards the horizon, right?

1073
00:57:41,208 --> 00:57:43,984
And the camera has got the horizon.

1074
00:57:47,748 --> 00:57:50,900
Then all of a sudden
we would see a little sail.

1075
00:57:52,369 --> 00:57:55,816
<i>And as soon as that sail
was in the shot, we had to stop</i>

1076
00:57:56,440 --> 00:58:00,650
and wait till it went
all the way across here,

1077
00:58:00,744 --> 00:58:02,644
which took an hour and a half.

1078
00:58:02,929 --> 00:58:05,739
And hope that at the end
of that hour and a half,

1079
00:58:05,832 --> 00:58:07,812
another one didn't come.

1080
00:58:08,235 --> 00:58:10,112
So we were always like…

1081
00:58:10,937 --> 00:58:14,771
As the sailing ship went off,

1082
00:58:15,759 --> 00:58:19,969
we were going, like, "Ready?
Speed. Action!

1083
00:58:20,047 --> 00:58:22,573
"No, there's another one!
Oh, God damn it!"

1084
00:58:23,583 --> 00:58:26,245
I mean, that put three hours
a day onto our schedule.

1085
00:58:26,319 --> 00:58:27,787
I'd sit there saying,

1086
00:58:27,854 --> 00:58:30,482
"Do I wait here for an
hour for the regatta to pass,

1087
00:58:30,674 --> 00:58:34,577
"or do we turn 18 to 25 anchors,

1088
00:58:34,678 --> 00:58:36,942
"move everything to look
in this direction?"

1089
00:58:37,047 --> 00:58:39,061
We used to do calculations and say,

1090
00:58:39,149 --> 00:58:42,210
"It'll take an hour for the
regatta to get from here to here,

1091
00:58:42,319 --> 00:58:44,310
"and an hour and 10 minutes

1092
00:58:44,421 --> 00:58:47,231
"to get all your anchors
and look back this way.

1093
00:58:47,874 --> 00:58:51,424
"Let's wait for the sailboats
to move out of the shot."

1094
00:58:51,611 --> 00:58:54,239
It was just frustrating for all of us.

1095
00:58:56,600 --> 00:58:58,762
<i>Everyone got seasick. Sooner or later,</i>

1096
00:58:58,869 --> 00:59:00,394
<i>everybody got seasick.</i>

1097
00:59:00,871 --> 00:59:04,819
Robert was really, really seasick one day.

1098
00:59:06,359 --> 00:59:09,442
And he had to shoot a line,
a very simple line.

1099
00:59:10,630 --> 00:59:14,077
The line was, "Hooper,
you idiot, ain't you watching?"

1100
00:59:14,367 --> 00:59:17,997
Okay? He had to be
helped into the chair.

1101
00:59:18,822 --> 00:59:21,200
And anyone touching him…

1102
00:59:21,274 --> 00:59:23,356
It hurt him just to be touched.

1103
00:59:25,095 --> 00:59:27,826
And we were all hoping that he'd get it.

1104
00:59:29,199 --> 00:59:33,477
Nobody was critical.
Nobody was mocking.

1105
00:59:33,553 --> 00:59:36,579
Nobody was standing apart
and pointing fingers.

1106
00:59:36,656 --> 00:59:40,741
We all knew exactly what he
was feeling. He just couldn't help it.

1107
00:59:42,395 --> 00:59:45,444
But we also knew that he
wouldn't be able to do this,

1108
00:59:45,549 --> 00:59:48,917
that this scene, however
small and of-the-moment,

1109
00:59:49,669 --> 00:59:51,660
would not get done today.

1110
00:59:54,024 --> 00:59:56,015
Steven set up the camera.

1111
00:59:56,226 --> 01:00:00,288
Robert was here, and he had to
turn into the camera to say this line.

1112
01:00:00,397 --> 01:00:04,300
He was… He literally… He went…

1113
01:00:16,329 --> 01:00:17,956
I mean, it hurt.

1114
01:00:19,416 --> 01:00:21,316
Steven said, "Action."

1115
01:00:22,586 --> 01:00:24,418
Robert turned around,

1116
01:00:24,521 --> 01:00:28,151
and with a power that
put me through the wall,

1117
01:00:28,525 --> 01:00:30,801
he went, "Hooper, you
idiot, ain't you watching?"

1118
01:00:30,894 --> 01:00:33,886
Ho open you idiot,
starboard! Ain't you watching it!

1119
01:00:34,080 --> 01:00:36,890
And I swear to God, everyone went…

1120
01:00:38,135 --> 01:00:41,332
And then Steven said, "Cut!
Print!" And Robert went…

1121
01:00:41,438 --> 01:00:42,917
Collapse.

1122
01:01:01,675 --> 01:01:03,302
You're going to need a bigger boat.

1123
01:01:03,376 --> 01:01:06,823
One of the most remembered
and oft-quoted lines in the movie

1124
01:01:06,930 --> 01:01:10,161
is Roy Scheider saying,
"We gotta get a bigger boat,"

1125
01:01:10,267 --> 01:01:11,883
which he improvised on the set,

1126
01:01:11,952 --> 01:01:13,420
and I acknowledge that as a writer.

1127
01:01:13,486 --> 01:01:14,783
I'm pleased that he said that.

1128
01:01:15,205 --> 01:01:18,015
The line, "We're gonna
need a bigger boat,"

1129
01:01:18,375 --> 01:01:21,652
has become part of the language

1130
01:01:22,028 --> 01:01:25,271
for people who are faced with
an insurmountable problem.

1131
01:01:35,559 --> 01:01:36,856
That's a 20-footer.

1132
01:01:36,927 --> 01:01:38,190
Twenty-five.

1133
01:01:38,862 --> 01:01:40,239
Three tons of him.

1134
01:01:40,330 --> 01:01:44,858
The studio was overloaded with
their own effects projects at the time,

1135
01:01:45,518 --> 01:01:47,498
<i>Hindenburg and Earthquake.</i>

1136
01:01:47,787 --> 01:01:49,767
Marshall Green, the
head of production, said,

1137
01:01:49,873 --> 01:01:52,524
"Take it, find someone to do it."

1138
01:01:52,976 --> 01:01:55,991
So I started interviewing
various effects people,

1139
01:01:56,062 --> 01:01:59,999
and I went to Disney's and other places

1140
01:02:00,066 --> 01:02:03,627
that do mechanical objects,

1141
01:02:03,703 --> 01:02:06,047
animals and what have you.

1142
01:02:06,323 --> 01:02:07,939
I wasn't having any luck.

1143
01:02:08,008 --> 01:02:09,954
Everybody was telling me,
"It can't be done.

1144
01:02:10,060 --> 01:02:12,529
"It would take three
years in development."

1145
01:02:12,629 --> 01:02:17,533
I heard about this guy that
had been retired for some time,

1146
01:02:17,968 --> 01:02:21,484
<i>who did the giant squid in</i>
20,000 <i>Leagues</i> Under <i>the Sea.</i>

1147
01:02:22,439 --> 01:02:24,555
<i>And his name was Bob Mattey.</i>

1148
01:02:25,292 --> 01:02:27,169
<i>So, when I met Bob,</i>

1149
01:02:27,277 --> 01:02:30,656
<i>I didn't get the usual
pessimistic attitude,</i>

1150
01:02:30,730 --> 01:02:32,243
<i>"You can't do this.</i>

1151
01:02:32,349 --> 01:02:36,092
<i>"You can't make this full-size
shark and shoot in the real ocean."</i>

1152
01:02:37,087 --> 01:02:38,885
Instead I got this very enthusiastic,

1153
01:02:38,989 --> 01:02:40,673
"Yes, we could do anything."

1154
01:02:42,142 --> 01:02:44,088
Probably

1155
01:02:45,095 --> 01:02:49,191
the reason that Steven and I decided,

1156
01:02:49,666 --> 01:02:51,828
in a naive sort of way,

1157
01:02:51,935 --> 01:02:55,371
that we were gonna build a full-size
shark and shoot the real ocean

1158
01:02:55,472 --> 01:02:57,952
and not a tank or not a miniature…

1159
01:02:59,643 --> 01:03:02,271
Maybe that was lack of
experience or whatever,

1160
01:03:02,379 --> 01:03:05,474
but everyone kept telling us
we couldn't do it.

1161
01:03:05,899 --> 01:03:08,015
So when I found Bob Mattey,

1162
01:03:08,118 --> 01:03:10,849
who actually had made
some of these giant creatures,

1163
01:03:10,954 --> 01:03:14,504
very enthusiastic about it,
it was very encouraging.

1164
01:03:36,246 --> 01:03:38,874
It had to be a formidable shark.

1165
01:03:40,250 --> 01:03:44,448
<i>And we made various sketches of
30-foot sharks and 20-foot sharks,</i>

1166
01:03:44,904 --> 01:03:47,783
<i>and came up with the… A
reasonable size would be 25 feet.</i>

1167
01:03:47,891 --> 01:03:51,088
<i>Very formidable, yet not Moby Dick.</i>

1168
01:03:51,795 --> 01:03:55,231
There have been sharks that have
been sighted that have been that size,

1169
01:03:55,332 --> 01:03:58,063
and they've actually caught
some that were 21 feet.

1170
01:03:58,168 --> 01:04:00,694
So it was a credible
animal we were making.

1171
01:04:00,804 --> 01:04:03,956
Doing the initial studies
of the great white shark,

1172
01:04:04,024 --> 01:04:06,322
I went to the Steinhardt

1173
01:04:06,393 --> 01:04:10,910
and I borrowed this set
of jaws which was huge.

1174
01:04:11,448 --> 01:04:14,349
It's an 18, 20-foot shark.

1175
01:04:14,751 --> 01:04:18,836
We made our shark larger
by another five or six feet,

1176
01:04:19,089 --> 01:04:21,615
but we kept everything in proportion.

1177
01:04:21,725 --> 01:04:25,821
Teeth. When I started
doing the actual drawings

1178
01:04:27,247 --> 01:04:30,046
for the construction of the shark,

1179
01:04:30,133 --> 01:04:32,875
we used everything in proper proportion.

1180
01:04:59,062 --> 01:05:01,292
Getting the right personnel
was sort of like…

1181
01:05:01,398 --> 01:05:02,695
<i>It reminds me of The Magnificent Seven</i>

1182
01:05:02,799 --> 01:05:05,234
where you're picking six great guys,

1183
01:05:05,335 --> 01:05:06,552
six big guns.

1184
01:05:09,406 --> 01:05:14,185
We heard of this young man
in the plastics section

1185
01:05:14,294 --> 01:05:16,137
by the name of Roy Arbogast.

1186
01:05:16,246 --> 01:05:17,873
He was an expert

1187
01:05:17,981 --> 01:05:21,144
on rubber forms and new
plastics, and things like that.

1188
01:05:21,618 --> 01:05:24,883
So we decided he would
be perfect to make the mold.

1189
01:05:24,988 --> 01:05:27,207
There was Richie Helmer and Bill Short,

1190
01:05:27,273 --> 01:05:29,742
who were excellent in electronics.

1191
01:05:30,994 --> 01:05:35,363
All this had to be
electrically-activated valves

1192
01:05:35,465 --> 01:05:38,844
that would work the rams
and various things of that type.

1193
01:05:38,918 --> 01:05:42,161
We were using hydraulics
instead of pneumatics because“.

1194
01:05:42,272 --> 01:05:45,583
Excuse me. We were using
pneumatics instead of hydraulics

1195
01:05:45,658 --> 01:05:48,252
because we didn't want
an oil break in the water.

1196
01:05:48,328 --> 01:05:50,319
So we had to get hydraulic experts too.

1197
01:05:50,447 --> 01:05:53,348
Then we had Mike and Gary
Woods, who were excellent welders.

1198
01:05:53,450 --> 01:05:55,498
<i>So we assembled this team,</i>

1199
01:05:56,019 --> 01:05:59,137
<i>and they started on
the frame of the shark.</i>

1200
01:05:59,873 --> 01:06:03,923
<i>So we were working from the
outside in and the inside out.</i>

1201
01:06:04,461 --> 01:06:06,452
<i>We were separately modeling the shark,</i>

1202
01:06:06,563 --> 01:06:09,464
<i>and then, at the same time,
they were making the skeleton,</i>

1203
01:06:09,566 --> 01:06:11,978
<i>and we hoped that
they would all fit together.</i>

1204
01:06:12,051 --> 01:06:13,394
<i>And there was a time element.</i>

1205
01:06:13,503 --> 01:06:15,403
<i>The time element was this…</i>

1206
01:06:15,505 --> 01:06:20,352
<i>It was that it was already
the first of the year in 1974,</i>

1207
01:06:20,944 --> 01:06:24,562
<i>and we knew we would have a
summer window in which to shoot this,</i>

1208
01:06:24,631 --> 01:06:26,622
<i>especially that we're gonna go back east.</i>

1209
01:06:26,733 --> 01:06:30,044
<i>We decided to shoot this in the
area it was written for, New England.</i>

1210
01:06:30,153 --> 01:06:32,622
So we had a time element there.

1211
01:06:33,740 --> 01:06:36,323
We built the shark
and tested the shark dry.

1212
01:06:51,391 --> 01:06:55,919
We were asked to make comments
about the mechanical shark,

1213
01:06:56,079 --> 01:06:58,764
and I think it helped them
to a certain extent.

1214
01:06:58,882 --> 01:07:03,570
Because I think they had too
much animation in the shark.

1215
01:07:04,003 --> 01:07:06,517
The shark, in reality,

1216
01:07:07,040 --> 01:07:09,987
moves in a very smooth, leisurely manner.

1217
01:07:10,143 --> 01:07:14,410
I can remember it sort of coming
up out of the water like that,

1218
01:07:14,531 --> 01:07:17,262
very fast vertically,
and they don't do that.

1219
01:07:17,367 --> 01:07:18,698
They sort of come up…

1220
01:07:20,303 --> 01:07:23,739
It's a slow… It's not really
slow, but it looks slow.

1221
01:07:24,023 --> 01:07:26,424
They took our advice,

1222
01:07:26,492 --> 01:07:29,735
and I know that it made a
big difference to the end result.

1223
01:07:43,810 --> 01:07:45,926
We had a number of
different shark components.

1224
01:07:46,029 --> 01:07:50,341
We had the full shark, which
I called the "great white turd."

1225
01:07:51,301 --> 01:07:53,736
We pulled it along in the water.

1226
01:07:53,820 --> 01:07:57,233
It was often on this huge
gantry like a crane arm.

1227
01:07:57,574 --> 01:08:00,657
When the crane arm was
tucked at the 30-foot bottom,

1228
01:08:00,727 --> 01:08:01,819
you couldn't see the shark.

1229
01:08:01,945 --> 01:08:05,563
But when the crane arm… As
quickly as they could blow the ballast

1230
01:08:05,632 --> 01:08:07,100
and force the arm out of the water,

1231
01:08:07,166 --> 01:08:09,476
the shark would rise out of the water.

1232
01:08:09,586 --> 01:08:12,362
The shark could be gimbaled
separately on the arm

1233
01:08:12,438 --> 01:08:15,738
to have an attitude change
at the top of the crane arm.

1234
01:08:15,808 --> 01:08:19,790
We had that. We had just a fin
that was pulled through the water.

1235
01:08:27,220 --> 01:08:30,702
We had a left-to-right shark
and a right-to-left shark.

1236
01:08:31,190 --> 01:08:33,750
The left-to-right shark, of course,

1237
01:08:34,193 --> 01:08:37,436
had no left side.
It was all scooped out.

1238
01:08:40,833 --> 01:08:43,097
<i>And vice versa for the other shark.</i>

1239
01:08:50,243 --> 01:08:53,087
Bob needed some area like this

1240
01:08:53,363 --> 01:08:56,879
that he could get all those hoses

1241
01:08:57,317 --> 01:08:59,001
and wires and stuff,

1242
01:08:59,152 --> 01:09:03,885
and have access to all
the mechanical stuff here.

1243
01:09:05,792 --> 01:09:07,635
Whatever needed to be repaired.

1244
01:09:07,744 --> 01:09:10,520
If we were shooting this
one with the hole here,

1245
01:09:10,596 --> 01:09:12,906
we could only shoot from the other side.

1246
01:09:13,016 --> 01:09:15,166
So this would be the left-to-right shark.

1247
01:09:15,234 --> 01:09:18,750
The idea still was to
try to convince the world

1248
01:09:19,339 --> 01:09:21,956
that we were using real sharks

1249
01:09:22,058 --> 01:09:23,901
or a great deal of real sharks.

1250
01:09:25,028 --> 01:09:29,272
So we didn't want the world to know

1251
01:09:29,716 --> 01:09:33,129
that the monster was really mechanical.

1252
01:09:34,520 --> 01:09:36,921
And also, we realized

1253
01:09:38,441 --> 01:09:41,775
that a mechanical monster
is only good when it moves.

1254
01:09:42,679 --> 01:09:45,922
When you take a still photograph of it,

1255
01:09:45,998 --> 01:09:49,445
it's gonna look phony under
the best of circumstances.

1256
01:09:54,624 --> 01:09:59,209
Somebody snuck in somehow into
the warehouse while we were shooting

1257
01:09:59,645 --> 01:10:02,376
and took a picture of one of the sharks.

1258
01:10:02,548 --> 01:10:06,109
And I remember getting
very agitated about that.

1259
01:10:09,539 --> 01:10:12,065
And none of us could understand,

1260
01:10:12,225 --> 01:10:16,059
because we really were very
careful about the secrecy element,

1261
01:10:16,129 --> 01:10:19,963
almost became paranoid about it.

1262
01:10:20,450 --> 01:10:23,397
But, in itself, the fact that

1263
01:10:24,087 --> 01:10:26,931
there was such secrecy surrounding this

1264
01:10:27,240 --> 01:10:29,334
created a great deal of interest.

1265
01:10:30,777 --> 01:10:33,895
That's a much-maligned shark,
and I'm kind of responsible

1266
01:10:33,980 --> 01:10:37,245
for creating a lot of the
badmouthing about the shark.

1267
01:10:37,316 --> 01:10:38,898
Because the shark was frustrating.

1268
01:10:38,985 --> 01:10:40,783
It didn't really work all the time.

1269
01:10:40,870 --> 01:10:42,304
It didn't work hardly at all.

1270
01:10:42,505 --> 01:10:47,159
I remember, in particular,
being on our barge,

1271
01:10:47,326 --> 01:10:50,318
watching the first shark test,

1272
01:10:51,063 --> 01:10:53,691
at which time the shark simply sank

1273
01:10:53,800 --> 01:10:56,326
to the bottom of Nantucket Sound.

1274
01:10:56,486 --> 01:11:00,434
And we felt that our careers in
motion pictures had gone with it.

1275
01:11:00,540 --> 01:11:04,704
Frogmen were delegated to recover
it and bring it back to the surface.

1276
01:11:04,894 --> 01:11:07,295
Everything that could
go wrong with a shark

1277
01:11:07,380 --> 01:11:09,439
went wrong with the various sharks,

1278
01:11:09,549 --> 01:11:11,643
the various types, head, fin, tails.

1279
01:11:11,717 --> 01:11:14,402
The ocean was so brutal on the mechanics.

1280
01:11:14,504 --> 01:11:15,915
All the pneumatic tubes,

1281
01:11:15,988 --> 01:11:20,858
all of that special equipment
was being dashed

1282
01:11:20,927 --> 01:11:23,555
and brutalized by the ocean every day.

1283
01:11:23,729 --> 01:11:27,097
There were all these radio
mikes all over the island,

1284
01:11:27,366 --> 01:11:29,812
the Universal radio mikes.

1285
01:11:30,186 --> 01:11:31,950
So wherever you were on the island,

1286
01:11:32,038 --> 01:11:34,200
you could hear the radio mikes.

1287
01:11:34,373 --> 01:11:35,863
They were always saying,

1288
01:11:35,942 --> 01:11:37,307
"The shark is not working.

1289
01:11:37,376 --> 01:11:40,835
"Repeat.
The shark is not working."

1290
01:11:41,581 --> 01:11:43,675
No matter where you were, and for months.

1291
01:11:43,749 --> 01:11:46,696
We just waited around.
We just waited and waited.

1292
01:11:46,803 --> 01:11:49,738
I remember every day, about
the 50th or 60th day of shooting,

1293
01:11:49,839 --> 01:11:52,331
the crew would come over
to me, and they'd all ask me,

1294
01:11:52,425 --> 01:11:54,484
"When are we going to
be done with this movie?"

1295
01:11:54,577 --> 01:11:56,488
And I would honestly say to them,

1296
01:11:56,596 --> 01:11:59,213
with complete sympathy for the question,

1297
01:11:59,949 --> 01:12:03,351
"I don't know. I don't know when
we're going to finish this movie.

1298
01:12:03,436 --> 01:12:06,895
"We could finish it if I get
fired and dragged off the movie.

1299
01:12:06,973 --> 01:12:10,238
"Somebody else could come and
finish it. Maybe they'll shut us down."

1300
01:12:11,878 --> 01:12:14,404
Show me the way to <i>go</i> home

1301
01:12:15,515 --> 01:12:18,143
<i>I'm tired and I want to go to bed</i>

1302
01:12:18,417 --> 01:12:20,818
<i>I had a little drink about an hour ago</i>

1303
01:12:20,887 --> 01:12:22,878
<i>And it's gone right to my head</i>

1304
01:12:23,422 --> 01:12:27,620
I remember how we got tears in
our eyes when we sang the song.

1305
01:12:27,693 --> 01:12:29,525
<i>Show me the way to go home</i>

1306
01:12:30,062 --> 01:12:32,690
<i>I'm tired and I want to go to bed</i>

1307
01:12:33,099 --> 01:12:35,659
Which is sung in the film
by the three principals.

1308
01:12:35,735 --> 01:12:39,046
I remember looking around
at Charlsie, the script girl,

1309
01:12:39,155 --> 01:12:41,749
and other people on the set
with tears in their eyes,

1310
01:12:41,858 --> 01:12:44,702
not because it was
a sweet, emotional scene.

1311
01:12:45,177 --> 01:12:46,986
That had become their mantra.

1312
01:12:47,079 --> 01:12:50,379
All they could think about
was, "What was home like?"

1313
01:12:50,533 --> 01:12:53,810
They missed their kids, and
they missed their backyards.

1314
01:12:54,170 --> 01:12:58,437
They missed their families
and their lifestyles.

1315
01:12:59,292 --> 01:13:03,092
And, in a sense, that's why I
always saw myself in the negative.

1316
01:13:03,195 --> 01:13:06,392
<i>I saw myself as James Cagney
in Mister Roberts,</i>

1317
01:13:06,465 --> 01:13:11,084
not letting the crew get to shore.

1318
01:13:11,254 --> 01:13:13,450
By the way, the crew did get to shore.

1319
01:13:13,556 --> 01:13:16,048
They got to shore every
Sunday that we had off.

1320
01:13:16,142 --> 01:13:17,576
We shot six-day weeks.

1321
01:13:17,660 --> 01:13:19,207
But I never left the island.

1322
01:13:19,312 --> 01:13:21,303
The reason I never left the island

1323
01:13:21,380 --> 01:13:24,463
in all those seven months of
shooting on Martha's Vineyard

1324
01:13:24,567 --> 01:13:26,376
was because if I left the island,

1325
01:13:26,485 --> 01:13:28,067
I was certain I would never come back.

1326
01:13:28,154 --> 01:13:30,202
The delays and the ocean

1327
01:13:30,306 --> 01:13:33,719
and the fact that we'd been on the
island for four or five months now,

1328
01:13:33,793 --> 01:13:36,569
we were all getting a little strange.

1329
01:13:37,697 --> 01:13:39,210
There was a…

1330
01:13:39,315 --> 01:13:43,309
I don't know if it was a charity
dinner or not, but it was a function,

1331
01:13:44,236 --> 01:13:47,399
a splendid buffet of wonderful food.

1332
01:13:47,657 --> 01:13:50,001
There was this tremendous
buffet of desserts,

1333
01:13:50,076 --> 01:13:52,545
strawberry shortcake and Boston cream pies

1334
01:13:52,612 --> 01:13:55,240
and chocolate eclairs and napoleons

1335
01:13:56,966 --> 01:14:00,812
and some Jell-O, and
also gravy and potatoes.

1336
01:14:00,886 --> 01:14:03,867
I'd said to Rick Fields,
who is Verna Fields' son,

1337
01:14:03,973 --> 01:14:06,089
"Suppose there was a food fight?"

1338
01:14:06,158 --> 01:14:07,990
And he said, "What do you mean?"

1339
01:14:08,077 --> 01:14:11,069
I said, "Well, you know, just
start throwing some food."

1340
01:14:11,163 --> 01:14:12,403
Roy started it.

1341
01:14:12,515 --> 01:14:17,260
Roy threw a big glob of mashed
potatoes and gravy right into my face,

1342
01:14:18,270 --> 01:14:21,103
and before I could recover
and throw something at him,

1343
01:14:21,173 --> 01:14:24,791
Richard Dreyfuss, I think, took his
dessert and threw it into Roy's face.

1344
01:14:24,894 --> 01:14:28,012
Right center, nose, eyes,
mouth, the whole thing.

1345
01:14:28,547 --> 01:14:31,744
Roy turned and he took two or
three desserts, threw them at Richard.

1346
01:14:31,817 --> 01:14:34,127
Richard ducked and it
hit somebody behind him,

1347
01:14:34,220 --> 01:14:36,655
and it was a bit of a Three Stooges brawl.

1348
01:14:36,739 --> 01:14:39,071
I remember Dick and David
got up and left right away.

1349
01:14:39,175 --> 01:14:40,859
They saw what was coming.

1350
01:14:40,926 --> 01:14:45,272
In about 30 seconds, we were actually
standing, hurling food at each other.

1351
01:14:45,381 --> 01:14:47,645
And it was a melee after that.

1352
01:14:48,017 --> 01:14:50,748
Just food all over the floor, all over…

1353
01:14:51,020 --> 01:14:54,570
The help that was there
serving dinner, they came out.

1354
01:14:54,874 --> 01:14:56,251
They laughed like crazy.

1355
01:14:56,359 --> 01:14:59,920
I don't know if some of the townspeople
appreciated it as much as we did,

1356
01:15:00,029 --> 01:15:03,556
but it was a tremendous
blowing off of steam.

1357
01:15:03,949 --> 01:15:06,941
I remember Richard and Roy,
covered in food,

1358
01:15:07,620 --> 01:15:09,452
running out to the Kelley
House swimming pool

1359
01:15:09,522 --> 01:15:11,263
and diving in the water.

1360
01:15:11,374 --> 01:15:14,321
And all this once-yummy food,

1361
01:15:14,777 --> 01:15:17,257
like Technicolor silt,

1362
01:15:17,329 --> 01:15:20,845
rising to the surface of this
otherwise turquoise pool.

1363
01:15:21,050 --> 01:15:22,779
I remember saying, "What
the heck," and I jumped in too,

1364
01:15:22,868 --> 01:15:25,530
and washed myself off.

1365
01:15:25,805 --> 01:15:27,705
But that was what happens in the Navy

1366
01:15:27,790 --> 01:15:29,804
when you just aren't given shore leave.

1367
01:15:29,875 --> 01:15:31,070
Let that be a lesson.

1368
01:15:31,160 --> 01:15:35,438
The decision to continue filming
Jaws was a very shaky one.

1369
01:15:36,332 --> 01:15:39,074
Our technical people,
what Steven Spielberg

1370
01:15:39,168 --> 01:15:42,547
was fond of calling "our
special defects department,"

1371
01:15:44,340 --> 01:15:47,253
wanted us to stop
so they could perfect it.

1372
01:15:48,811 --> 01:15:53,658
Dick and I, battle-scarred
veterans of the movie wars,

1373
01:15:53,733 --> 01:15:57,681
knew that you never take
the film out of the camera

1374
01:15:57,787 --> 01:16:00,028
because they may never
let you put it back,

1375
01:16:00,106 --> 01:16:02,040
particularly with a movie like this.

1376
01:16:02,108 --> 01:16:06,818
Even if we got one-sixteenth of a
page of script a day, you kept moving.

1377
01:16:07,997 --> 01:16:12,047
Steven, at one point, considered
moving our whole crew to the Bahamas,

1378
01:16:12,118 --> 01:16:14,416
where the waters were
tranquil and everything,

1379
01:16:14,487 --> 01:16:16,421
and we weren't in favor of that.

1380
01:16:16,489 --> 01:16:18,435
"Just keep shooting.

1381
01:16:18,541 --> 01:16:21,283
"Keep shooting and make do
with what you've got."

1382
01:16:21,393 --> 01:16:24,693
This whole system with the barrels,

1383
01:16:24,764 --> 01:16:26,277
that kept the shark alive.

1384
01:16:26,482 --> 01:16:30,225
<i>When those barrels came up,
the shark was there,</i>

1385
01:16:30,553 --> 01:16:32,237
and that really saved us.

1386
01:16:32,505 --> 01:16:36,339
It saved us, or we'd still be there
waiting for the shark to work, really.

1387
01:16:36,408 --> 01:16:39,503
Finally, after all this,
it was maybe September,

1388
01:16:39,578 --> 01:16:42,297
we got the shark to
raise out of the water.

1389
01:16:42,398 --> 01:16:45,129
That was that one shot with Roy Scheider,

1390
01:16:45,768 --> 01:16:47,350
and it just barely worked.

1391
01:16:47,520 --> 01:16:48,612
Okay.

1392
01:16:50,406 --> 01:16:52,522
Good blood.
And action, Roy.

1393
01:16:52,591 --> 01:16:53,717
Slow ahead.

1394
01:16:53,793 --> 01:16:55,409
I can go slow ahead.

1395
01:16:55,511 --> 01:16:58,572
You ought to come down
and ladle some of this shit.

1396
01:17:02,968 --> 01:17:04,060
<i>And down!</i>

1397
01:17:10,376 --> 01:17:11,434
<i>And cut!</i>

1398
01:17:11,694 --> 01:17:15,426
And then one day you heard
this, "The shark is working.

1399
01:17:16,265 --> 01:17:18,256
"Repeat.
The shark is working."

1400
