01:29:29,714 --> 01:29:32,206
So he said, "Here is
what I propose to do."

1630
01:29:32,284 --> 01:29:34,161
And he told me the ending he had in mind.

1631
01:29:34,269 --> 01:29:38,456
I said, "Steven, that is completely
unbelievable. It can't happen.

1632
01:29:38,607 --> 01:29:43,272
"A shark does not bite down on a scuba
tank and explode like an oil refinery."

1633
01:29:44,362 --> 01:29:46,353
He said, "I don't care."

1634
01:29:46,731 --> 01:29:49,450
He said, "if I have
got them for two hours,

1635
01:29:49,551 --> 01:29:51,133
"they will believe whatever I do

1636
01:29:51,202 --> 01:29:53,933
"for the next three minutes,
because I've got them.

1637
01:29:54,022 --> 01:29:58,289
"I want the audience on
their feet screaming at the end,

1638
01:29:58,410 --> 01:30:01,846
"'Yes, yes! This is what
should happen to this animal!"'

1639
01:30:01,947 --> 01:30:05,406
Which reminded me, in
retrospect, of the Bill Goldman thing,

1640
01:30:05,483 --> 01:30:09,067
which is that reality may be
great and truth may be wonderful,

1641
01:30:09,154 --> 01:30:12,067
but none of it holds a
candle to believability.

1642
01:30:12,157 --> 01:30:14,057
If the filmmaker has done his job

1643
01:30:14,125 --> 01:30:17,686
and brought you into
believability, he can do anything.

1644
01:30:17,846 --> 01:30:21,430
Play by the rules. Set the
rules, but follow the rules.

1645
01:30:21,499 --> 01:30:23,684
And that's exactly what Steven did.

1646
01:30:23,952 --> 01:30:25,534
He was right, I was wrong,

1647
01:30:25,604 --> 01:30:27,015
in this entire argument.

1648
01:30:27,589 --> 01:30:31,275
His ending brought people
to their feet screaming,

1649
01:30:31,343 --> 01:30:33,857
"Yes, yes! This is
the way it should be!"

1650
01:30:34,062 --> 01:30:37,965
And it may be incredible,
but it was the right thing to do.

1651
01:30:44,673 --> 01:30:46,607
Smile, you son of a bitch!

1652
01:30:59,437 --> 01:31:01,565
In <i>Duel,</i> you hear the sound of…

1653
01:31:01,690 --> 01:31:05,354
In fact it was a dinosaur growling

1654
01:31:05,744 --> 01:31:07,644
from an old "B" dinosaur picture,

1655
01:31:07,729 --> 01:31:09,379
when the truck went over the cliff,

1656
01:31:09,447 --> 01:31:13,816
'cause I had always imagined the truck
to be a bit like a T-rex chasing a car.

1657
01:31:27,115 --> 01:31:29,925
I used the very same sound effect in <i>Jaws</i>.

1658
01:31:30,468 --> 01:31:32,960
Almost as a bit of just a reminder

1659
01:31:33,038 --> 01:31:36,918
that there was a kinship
between both stories,

1660
01:31:37,308 --> 01:31:39,777
as the shark is sinking to
the bottom of the ocean,

1661
01:31:39,844 --> 01:31:42,779
<i>after it's been exploded
by the compressed air.</i>

1662
01:32:07,338 --> 01:32:11,684
<i>One of the great
pieces of Spielbergian genius</i>

1663
01:32:12,227 --> 01:32:15,686
was the fact that at the
end of the movie Jaws,

1664
01:32:16,164 --> 01:32:18,599
the Richard Dreyfuss character pops up

1665
01:32:19,067 --> 01:32:20,967
and they swim to shore together.

1666
01:32:21,069 --> 01:32:22,810
<i>This brought cheers, of course.</i>

1667
01:32:22,887 --> 01:32:24,867
<i>It was what the audience wanted.</i>

1668
01:32:26,357 --> 01:32:28,086
I used to hate the water.

1669
01:32:30,361 --> 01:32:32,341
I can't imagine why.

1670
01:32:33,898 --> 01:32:36,083
<i>When I finally did leave the island,</i>

1671
01:32:36,184 --> 01:32:39,882
just before the last shot, which
was the blowing up of the shark…

1672
01:32:40,271 --> 01:32:41,739
I left the island for two reasons.

1673
01:32:41,823 --> 01:32:44,474
One, I heard the crew wanted
to throw me overboard.

1674
01:32:44,542 --> 01:32:48,888
I didn't know whether they were going
to throw me overboard in cement slippers

1675
01:32:48,997 --> 01:32:52,900
or throw me overboard via the poop deck,

1676
01:32:53,001 --> 01:32:54,742
one bounce, and then into the water.

1677
01:32:54,836 --> 01:32:58,682
Or whether it was going
to be just into the water

1678
01:32:58,757 --> 01:32:59,997
with a two-foot sandy bottom.

1679
01:33:00,108 --> 01:33:01,371
I didn't know what they were gonna do,

1680
01:33:01,476 --> 01:33:03,467
so I thought I'd get out quickly.

1681
01:33:03,561 --> 01:33:06,007
I remember when I got to Boston

1682
01:33:06,648 --> 01:33:08,742
on the ferry.

1683
01:33:10,034 --> 01:33:13,231
We spent the night in Boston, and
the next day we were scheduled…

1684
01:33:13,304 --> 01:33:16,649
Dreyfuss and I had to fly back to
Los Angeles on American Airlines.

1685
01:33:16,758 --> 01:33:20,194
I vividly recall
getting into my hotel room

1686
01:33:21,129 --> 01:33:26,033
and having a complete anxiety breakdown.

1687
01:33:26,134 --> 01:33:27,568
I mean it's a complete…

1688
01:33:27,669 --> 01:33:30,297
I don't know what you would
call it. It was a breakdown.

1689
01:33:30,405 --> 01:33:32,100
I couldn't stop shaking.

1690
01:33:32,357 --> 01:33:35,054
My jaw was clenched.
I couldn't open my mouth.

1691
01:33:35,326 --> 01:33:37,260
I was getting electrical
shocks through my brain

1692
01:33:37,328 --> 01:33:38,944
like I was having seizures.

1693
01:33:39,047 --> 01:33:40,788
I know this sounds really melodramatic,

1694
01:33:40,882 --> 01:33:42,407
but it's exactly what happened.

1695
01:33:42,517 --> 01:33:44,747
Something neurological, emotional…

1696
01:33:44,853 --> 01:33:46,196
Something was happening to me.

1697
01:33:46,271 --> 01:33:49,263
It was a full panic attack,

1698
01:33:49,340 --> 01:33:54,323
which I don't remember ever
having at that level before.

1699
01:33:55,263 --> 01:33:56,890
I remember calling Richard up.

1700
01:33:56,981 --> 01:34:00,690
He was in the pub downstairs
and Richard came up with me.

1701
01:34:00,902 --> 01:34:03,018
I just said, "I'm in
really bad shape, Ricky."

1702
01:34:03,087 --> 01:34:06,387
Rick said, "Don't worry. We'll be on
the airplane tomorrow." Which we were.

1703
01:34:06,724 --> 01:34:10,968
My recollection is that we
showed a cut version of the film

1704
01:34:11,980 --> 01:34:14,711
with one big sequence missing,

1705
01:34:14,816 --> 01:34:16,545
without Johnny Williams' music,

1706
01:34:16,985 --> 01:34:19,613
in a projection room at Universal Studios.

1707
01:34:20,305 --> 01:34:24,993
And when the lights went on, there
was no reaction at all, as I recall.

1708
01:34:25,827 --> 01:34:28,421
I recall turning around and saying,

1709
01:34:28,530 --> 01:34:30,430
"Well, Sid, what do you think?"

1710
01:34:30,532 --> 01:34:32,000
He said, "It's okay."

1711
01:34:32,100 --> 01:34:35,365
Well, "okay" was like
being given one-half a star.

1712
01:34:35,687 --> 01:34:38,463
"Okay" for 159 days?

1713
01:34:38,573 --> 01:34:40,223
Of course it was only "okay."

1714
01:34:40,575 --> 01:34:42,805
It didn't have Johnny Williams' music.

1715
01:34:42,911 --> 01:34:46,370
It didn't have some major underwater stuff

1716
01:34:46,481 --> 01:34:49,007
that we filmed in the tank at MGM Studios

1717
01:34:49,117 --> 01:34:51,916
in order to get very
close angles underwater.

1718
01:34:52,020 --> 01:34:53,020
We couldn't get…

1719
01:34:53,071 --> 01:34:55,722
The waters in Martha's
Vineyard, both cold and murky,

1720
01:34:55,807 --> 01:34:58,174
wouldn't allow us to do
much underwater stuff.

1721
01:34:58,243 --> 01:35:02,225
Metro had this great Esther
Williams tank, as it used to be called.

1722
01:35:02,864 --> 01:35:06,607
So the reaction was, "Go
get the rest of the movie."

1723
01:35:06,684 --> 01:35:08,925
When they came back
from Martha's Vineyard,

1724
01:35:09,037 --> 01:35:10,766
they realized that they didn't have

1725
01:35:10,872 --> 01:35:12,283
the footage, as I understood it,

1726
01:35:12,357 --> 01:35:16,772
that they needed, of Hooper
and the shark together in the cage.

1727
01:35:17,212 --> 01:35:18,509
So I was called.

1728
01:35:18,613 --> 01:35:21,355
A friend of mine, Jesse
Wayne, recommended me.

1729
01:35:21,432 --> 01:35:25,209
He was called first, and, not
being a certified scuba diver,

1730
01:35:25,470 --> 01:35:29,782
he spoke to Tom Joyner, the
assistant director, who then called me.

1731
01:35:29,991 --> 01:35:31,265
I went in,

1732
01:35:31,542 --> 01:35:35,160
and we went down to Culver City

1733
01:35:35,263 --> 01:35:38,631
to MGM Studios, and
shot it in a tank down there.

1734
01:35:51,496 --> 01:35:54,181
There were three inter-cuts
for the sequence

1735
01:35:54,282 --> 01:35:55,977
where the shark attacks the cage.

1736
01:35:56,084 --> 01:35:59,736
One, of course, was Dick Warlock,

1737
01:36:00,305 --> 01:36:05,106
who was the stunt person inside
the cage subbing for Richard Dreyfuss.

1738
01:36:08,630 --> 01:36:12,510
<i>The second was the Rizzo
shoot with Ron and Val in Australia.</i>

1739
01:36:13,201 --> 01:36:16,785
And there was Frank Sparks,
whose eyes I actually used

1740
01:36:16,854 --> 01:36:18,629
to substitute Richard's eyes

1741
01:36:18,740 --> 01:36:20,890
because Rich was unavailable
for shooting the inserts.

1742
01:36:20,959 --> 01:36:23,439
So when you see
the Richard Dreyfuss scream,

1743
01:36:23,528 --> 01:36:26,270
that's not Richard's face,
those aren't Richard's eyes.

1744
01:36:26,381 --> 01:36:28,110
<i>That's a guy named Sparks.</i>

1745
01:36:36,291 --> 01:36:37,417
Help!

1746
01:36:38,142 --> 01:36:42,022
Down in the tank was a metal apparatus

1747
01:36:42,130 --> 01:36:44,224
that the shark was attached to,

1748
01:36:44,432 --> 01:36:49,177
where it could move forward,
backward, sideways, up and down.

1749
01:36:49,454 --> 01:36:52,503
So it had pretty good
movement, real natural movement.

1750
01:36:52,890 --> 01:36:54,722
<i>It was operated by a special effects man.</i>

1751
01:36:54,792 --> 01:36:56,442
<i>His name is Whitey Krumm.</i>

1752
01:37:35,717 --> 01:37:37,446
As Whitey was looking in one window,

1753
01:37:37,552 --> 01:37:40,544
watching the shark from
the side with the controls,

1754
01:37:40,671 --> 01:37:42,446
Mr. Spielberg was around the other side,

1755
01:37:42,557 --> 01:37:44,286
or a quarter of the way around,

1756
01:37:44,392 --> 01:37:46,087
looking at it from another perspective.

1757
01:37:46,194 --> 01:37:49,038
He was looking at the shark
coming directly at the cage,

1758
01:37:49,130 --> 01:37:51,815
and they communicated with each other

1759
01:37:51,883 --> 01:37:54,102
via headphones and a microphone.

1760
01:37:54,202 --> 01:37:56,614
<i>Okay, here we go. Attack.</i>

1761
01:38:04,312 --> 01:38:05,837
<i>Bring it out now!</i>

1762
01:38:05,947 --> 01:38:06,994
<i>Bring it out!</i>

1763
01:38:07,632 --> 01:38:10,215
<i>Okay, attack!
Attack!</i>

1764
01:38:15,540 --> 01:38:17,474
<i>Okay, bring it back and bring it in again.</i>

1765
01:38:17,542 --> 01:38:19,692
<i>Bring it back and then bring it in.</i>

1766
01:38:26,401 --> 01:38:27,641
<i>Yeah, bring it out!</i>

1767
01:38:27,769 --> 01:38:29,009
<i>Bring it out!</i>

1768
01:38:30,138 --> 01:38:31,333
<i>Now bring it in.</i>

1769
01:38:31,439 --> 01:38:32,770
<i>Bring it in again.</i>

1770
01:38:33,257 --> 01:38:37,569
<i>Now, cut!
Once again, right</i> away.

1771
01:38:37,662 --> 01:38:39,505
<i>Yeah, next time. Okay?</i>

1772
01:38:41,983 --> 01:38:44,293
Good grief.
Am I in trouble with <i>Jaws?</i>

1773
01:38:45,036 --> 01:38:46,504
In Jaws trouble?

1774
01:38:46,571 --> 01:38:49,131
Verna was great. We used to call her…

1775
01:38:49,207 --> 01:38:52,518
Our affectionate nickname for
Verna Fields was "Mother Cutter"

1776
01:38:52,627 --> 01:38:56,530
because she was like our
mom and she cooked for us,

1777
01:38:56,681 --> 01:38:59,992
and she told us great
stories of Peter Bogdanovich

1778
01:39:00,101 --> 01:39:02,320
and all the films that she cut with him.

1779
01:39:02,437 --> 01:39:03,848
She was just a great person.

1780
01:39:03,921 --> 01:39:05,855
She was a very charismatic person.

1781
01:39:05,923 --> 01:39:09,700
She was the most charismatic
person on Jaws, her and Robert Shaw.

1782
01:39:09,811 --> 01:39:11,427
Except she never came out to sea.

1783
01:39:11,496 --> 01:39:13,055
She was always in her cutting room.

1784
01:39:13,181 --> 01:39:15,866
It was frustrating for
Verna, for two reasons.

1785
01:39:15,967 --> 01:39:18,334
One, she never had enough film to cut.

1786
01:39:18,453 --> 01:39:20,865
Because on a good day, I get five shots.

1787
01:39:20,938 --> 01:39:23,032
On a good day at sea, five shots.

1788
01:39:23,307 --> 01:39:26,504
On an average day, about
three. On a bad day, none.

1789
01:39:27,345 --> 01:39:31,077
Verna didn't have a lot of film racing
into her cutting room to put together,

1790
01:39:31,199 --> 01:39:33,543
so she had to be on the
island for seven months,

1791
01:39:33,618 --> 01:39:34,995
with very little to cut.

1792
01:39:35,086 --> 01:39:37,771
<i>Verna didn't have the film
until we finished the movie.</i>

1793
01:39:37,872 --> 01:39:39,522
<i>That's when Verna's work got started.</i>

1794
01:39:39,607 --> 01:39:42,292
<i>Verna and I worked every day
on the picture at her house,</i>

1795
01:39:42,360 --> 01:39:47,207
<i>in her little cutting room by
the pool, and she did a great job.</i>

1796
01:39:49,000 --> 01:39:50,115
What am I looking for?

1797
01:39:50,218 --> 01:39:54,337
We're looking for a nice place to
show that Quint refuses to slow the boat.

1798
01:40:03,498 --> 01:40:05,910
<i>Quint, it can't take that much pressure!</i>

1799
01:40:08,286 --> 01:40:09,651
That's the spot, Steve.

1800
01:40:09,971 --> 01:40:13,748
I had always wanted to be in
business with John Williams, all my life.

1801
01:40:14,292 --> 01:40:17,341
When he said yes to Sugar
land, and we became friends…

1802
01:40:18,129 --> 01:40:20,120
Obviously, I wanted him to
do every picture I ever made,

1803
01:40:20,248 --> 01:40:22,228
and Jaws came second.

1804
01:40:22,300 --> 01:40:25,600
When John saw the movie,
he called me up on the phone.

1805
01:40:25,670 --> 01:40:27,934
He said, "This is like a pirate movie."

1806
01:40:28,005 --> 01:40:30,565
And he said, "I think we
need pirate music for this

1807
01:40:30,658 --> 01:40:33,969
"because this is primal, but
it's also fun and entertaining."

1808
01:40:34,045 --> 01:40:36,889
This idea of characterizing
the shark musically,

1809
01:40:36,998 --> 01:40:40,684
these low, thumping
ostinato notes in the bass,

1810
01:40:41,736 --> 01:40:44,467
were the result of a very
simple idea that I had.

1811
01:40:44,572 --> 01:40:48,691
I thought that the shark
should be represented

1812
01:40:48,793 --> 01:40:50,989
by something in sound or in music,

1813
01:40:51,062 --> 01:40:55,056
probably music, because there's no
sound underneath the water, we thought.

1814
01:40:55,550 --> 01:40:57,427
Today you might do it with sound effects.

1815
01:40:57,501 --> 01:41:00,277
I thought a driving thing in
the bottom of the orchestra

1816
01:41:00,388 --> 01:41:05,235
might indicate the
mindless attack of the shark.

1817
01:41:05,326 --> 01:41:08,921
It's all instinct. There's no
real intelligence behind it.

1818
01:41:09,931 --> 01:41:11,558
It's an unstoppable…

1819
01:41:12,817 --> 01:41:17,414
This thing comes at you. You
can't fight it off without destroying it

1820
01:41:17,888 --> 01:41:20,664
because of this
relentless drive that it has.

1821
01:41:20,825 --> 01:41:24,659
When he finally played the
music for me on the piano,

1822
01:41:24,729 --> 01:41:27,198
he previewed the main Jaws theme.

1823
01:41:27,531 --> 01:41:31,195
I expected to hear something
kind of weird and melodic,

1824
01:41:32,320 --> 01:41:36,052
kind of tonal, but eerie
and of another world,

1825
01:41:36,157 --> 01:41:38,842
almost a bit like outer space,

1826
01:41:38,960 --> 01:41:40,735
inner space under the water.

1827
01:41:41,545 --> 01:41:43,206
And what he played me instead,

1828
01:41:43,281 --> 01:41:45,545
with two fingers on the lower keys, was…

1829
01:41:48,603 --> 01:41:50,947
At first I began to laugh.
I thought he was…

1830
01:41:51,022 --> 01:41:53,866
He had a great sense of humor.
I thought he was putting me on.

1831
01:41:53,975 --> 01:41:56,558
And he said, "No, that's
the theme to Jaws!"

1832
01:41:57,228 --> 01:41:59,754
I said, "Play it again."
He played it again.

1833
01:42:00,231 --> 01:42:04,145
And he played it again,
and it suddenly seemed right.

1834
01:42:04,235 --> 01:42:06,397
But when I first heard it, it seemed wrong

1835
01:42:06,470 --> 01:42:09,986
because it just seemed too simple.

1836
01:42:10,574 --> 01:42:15,239
And so simple… Often the
best ideas are the simplest ones.

1837
01:42:15,780 --> 01:42:19,614
And John found a signature
for the entire movie.

1838
01:42:19,684 --> 01:42:23,086
One could alter
the speed of this ostinato.

1839
01:42:23,154 --> 01:42:25,566
It could be note, note,

1840
01:42:25,673 --> 01:42:28,802
any kind of alteration
of speed, to very slow,

1841
01:42:28,893 --> 01:42:31,635
very fast, very soft, very loud.

1842
01:42:31,896 --> 01:42:35,958
All these things could
manipulate the moment

1843
01:42:36,384 --> 01:42:39,115
to illustrate that the shark was

1844
01:42:39,954 --> 01:42:43,800
at the highest pitch of
frenzy, or something lower.

1845
01:42:44,442 --> 01:42:48,174
And this simple dramatic device
seemed to be what we needed.

1846
01:43:27,284 --> 01:43:28,945
<i>Part of the genius of John Williams</i>

1847
01:43:29,019 --> 01:43:33,217
is how he spots music and
how he places music in a movie.

1848
01:43:33,374 --> 01:43:35,854
That's sort of something

1849
01:43:35,960 --> 01:43:38,861
that's never discussed
about the art of composition.

1850
01:43:39,497 --> 01:43:41,659
The placement of that composition.

1851
01:43:42,333 --> 01:43:46,816
And John did not want music
to celebrate a red herring.

1852
01:43:47,138 --> 01:43:50,597
He only wanted music to signal
the actual arrival of the shark.

1853
01:43:54,612 --> 01:43:59,413
<i>There were opportunities
to advertise the shark with music,</i>

1854
01:43:59,784 --> 01:44:02,264
<i>and also opportunities
when we don't have the music</i>

1855
01:44:02,353 --> 01:44:04,947
<i>and the audience has
the sense of an absence.</i>

1856
01:44:07,508 --> 01:44:10,626
They sense the absence of the
shark. They don't hear the thump.

1857
01:44:10,694 --> 01:44:12,788
We've conditioned them to do that.

1858
01:44:17,752 --> 01:44:19,527
<i>But then you may go one step further.</i>

1859
01:44:19,603 --> 01:44:21,753
<i>We know now the shark really is there,</i>

1860
01:44:21,856 --> 01:44:23,574
<i>but we haven't advertised it with music,</i>

1861
01:44:23,641 --> 01:44:25,803
<i>so his attack comes out of silence.</i>

1862
01:44:27,128 --> 01:44:30,029
<i>Now, because you're conditioned
to have the music every time,</i>

1863
01:44:30,131 --> 01:44:33,647
<i>when you don't and the shark
arrives, it's even more terrifying.</i>

1864
01:44:34,552 --> 01:44:36,850
It's one of the beauties
of the film medium

1865
01:44:36,921 --> 01:44:40,221
that when you combine music
with this kind of visual thing,

1866
01:44:40,291 --> 01:44:42,988
you can get this association
in people's minds.

1867
01:44:43,093 --> 01:44:46,358
I think if you did it musically
just in a concert piece,

1868
01:44:46,464 --> 01:44:48,193
it wouldn't have the same effect.

1869
01:44:48,265 --> 01:44:52,224
It's the combination of
the visual and the situation.

1870
01:44:52,303 --> 01:44:56,149
This being the shark, or the
knifing scene in Hitchcock's Psycho,

1871
01:44:56,307 --> 01:44:57,502
combined with the notes.

1872
01:44:57,575 --> 01:45:02,308
That combination of sound and image

1873
01:45:02,563 --> 01:45:04,190
forming a memory,

1874
01:45:04,415 --> 01:45:08,579
which can then be referred back to.

1875
01:45:08,936 --> 01:45:11,098
As you do with an
audience that now hears it,

1876
01:45:11,205 --> 01:45:13,003
and a child will scream in terror

1877
01:45:13,107 --> 01:45:16,589
because of the association
that's been created.

1878
01:45:16,660 --> 01:45:18,321
Ho open where are you?

1879
01:45:20,848 --> 01:45:23,966
<i>My favorite cue in</i> Jaws
<i>has always been that barrel chase,</i>

1880
01:45:24,034 --> 01:45:27,595
<i>where the shark approaches the
boat and they harpoon the animal</i>

1881
01:45:27,671 --> 01:45:32,404
<i>and he takes the line out
and the barrels lift off the boat</i>

1882
01:45:32,510 --> 01:45:35,411
<i>and the music accelerates
and becomes very exciting.</i>

1883
01:45:36,146 --> 01:45:37,307
<i>Show.</i>

1884
01:45:40,317 --> 01:45:41,409
Time.

1885
01:45:43,153 --> 01:45:44,735
What were you doing? You knew I had

1886
01:45:44,839 --> 01:45:47,137
to get a clean shot right in the head.

1887
01:45:47,241 --> 01:45:50,723
All right, let's see how long
that barrel takes to bring him up.

1888
01:45:50,794 --> 01:45:54,981
The boat turns to follow the
shark as he's pulling the line out,

1889
01:45:55,065 --> 01:45:56,624
and the music becomes very heroic.

1890
01:45:56,700 --> 01:46:01,103
There's a Korngoldian
fanfare, if you like, of triumph

1891
01:46:01,171 --> 01:46:04,618
as they're going through
the waves chasing the shark.

1892
01:46:05,626 --> 01:46:08,812
Bring another barrel!
I'm coming around again!

1893
01:46:25,362 --> 01:46:27,387
<i>Suddenly the shark dives down.</i>

1894
01:46:27,464 --> 01:46:31,560
<i>The music deflates and gets
slower and slower and softer.</i>

1895
01:46:35,839 --> 01:46:38,820
<i>The deflation and
disappointment of the realization</i>

1896
01:46:38,926 --> 01:46:41,111
<i>that the shark hasn't been captured.</i>

1897
01:46:41,562 --> 01:46:46,216
It's all illustrated in this
one area where the music

1898
01:46:46,750 --> 01:46:50,778
is able to follow all that
dramatic outline and punctuate it.

1899
01:46:50,905 --> 01:46:52,737
Without that score,

1900
01:46:52,840 --> 01:46:55,434
I believe the film would have
only been half as successful.

1901
01:46:55,526 --> 01:46:58,962
The score was clearly responsible
for half the success of that movie.

1902
01:46:59,046 --> 01:47:03,791
<i>Jaws</i> certainly was a hallmark in
my career. It changed it very greatly.

1903
01:47:03,867 --> 01:47:05,062
I had done

1904
01:47:05,135 --> 01:47:08,070
I don't know how many films,
dozens, before that,

1905
01:47:08,138 --> 01:47:10,288
and certainly hundreds
of television shows.

1906
01:47:10,391 --> 01:47:13,406
As a matter of fact, I'd even won
an Academy Award before Jaws

1907
01:47:13,510 --> 01:47:16,172
<i>for having been</i> music
<i>director of Fiddler on the Roof,</i>

1908
01:47:16,246 --> 01:47:19,511
for which I did all the
arrangements and underscoring

1909
01:47:19,617 --> 01:47:23,611
and conducting of that
movie in 1970, I think it was.

1910
01:47:25,356 --> 01:47:30,066
Jaws, for me, was the first Academy
Award that I received for my own music.

1911
01:47:31,245 --> 01:47:35,091
So that was a very significant
moment in my career,

1912
01:47:35,165 --> 01:47:37,247
as it would be for anyone's.

1913
01:47:37,368 --> 01:47:39,894
The first test of Jaws took place,

1914
01:47:40,437 --> 01:47:44,101
as I wrote in my own book,
in Dallas in a shopping center.

1915
01:47:46,894 --> 01:47:49,989
Dick Zanuck and I were extremely nervous.

1916
01:47:50,364 --> 01:47:52,446
Would the shark get laughs?

1917
01:47:52,816 --> 01:47:56,650
Everybody knew that had read a
newspaper, that it was not a real shark.

1918
01:47:57,104 --> 01:47:58,697
What would happen?

1919
01:47:58,806 --> 01:48:02,458
And I remember circling
around that theater,

1920
01:48:03,293 --> 01:48:04,920
and we noticed a crowd.

1921
01:48:05,195 --> 01:48:09,177
Of course we weren't very subtle
with what was put on the marquee.

1922
01:48:09,283 --> 01:48:11,866
It was like, "The biggest
fish story you'll ever see,"

1923
01:48:11,935 --> 01:48:15,280
or something very clever
that attracted attention.

1924
01:48:15,389 --> 01:48:17,403
After all, Jaws was
a number one bestseller

1925
01:48:17,474 --> 01:48:19,408
and had a lot of media attention.

1926
01:48:19,476 --> 01:48:22,923
And so we went and had a very stiff drink.

1927
01:48:23,847 --> 01:48:25,656
We went into the theater,

1928
01:48:25,949 --> 01:48:28,680
and the screams started,
and they never stopped.

1929
01:48:29,136 --> 01:48:32,049
And we were pinching
each other. It was incredible.

1930
01:48:32,256 --> 01:48:36,215
I thought the whole roof,

1931
01:48:36,326 --> 01:48:39,307
ceiling of the theater
was going to collapse

1932
01:48:39,413 --> 01:48:43,600
because of the noise, the
shock and the screams so loud.

1933
01:48:44,418 --> 01:48:46,580
And it didn't die down, so that we…

1934
01:48:46,687 --> 01:48:51,124
You couldn't, literally, hear the dialogue

1935
01:48:51,225 --> 01:48:54,786
for the next, maybe minute
because there was…

1936
01:48:54,878 --> 01:48:57,506
People were screaming repeatedly.

1937
01:48:58,165 --> 01:49:01,066
And there was such
excitement in the theater.

1938
01:49:01,335 --> 01:49:05,920
I remember elbowing Mr. Brown,
who was sitting next to me,

1939
01:49:07,458 --> 01:49:10,974
and he was elbowing me back,
and said, "We're in. We did it."

1940
01:49:11,345 --> 01:49:15,088
We knew with that first
scream that it had worked.

1941
01:49:15,182 --> 01:49:17,344
When the shark came out of the water,

1942
01:49:17,451 --> 01:49:19,351
when Roy Scheider was chumming and said,

1943
01:49:19,453 --> 01:49:22,036
"Why don't you come down
and chum some of this shit?"

1944
01:49:22,106 --> 01:49:23,619
The shark comes out.

1945
01:49:23,724 --> 01:49:27,354
I had designed, hopefully, a
laugh that would turn into a scream.

1946
01:49:27,461 --> 01:49:29,839
So I used the word "shit."
I added that line

1947
01:49:29,913 --> 01:49:32,257
because in those days, back in 1974,

1948
01:49:32,366 --> 01:49:33,629
the word "shit" was an easy laugh.

1949
01:49:33,734 --> 01:49:35,543
Now it's used so much
nobody laughs anymore.

1950
01:49:35,652 --> 01:49:37,416
Then it wasn't used that much.

1951
01:49:37,488 --> 01:49:39,707
It instantly got a nervous
laugh from audiences,

1952
01:49:39,807 --> 01:49:43,641
often an embarrassed laugh. With
younger people, a rebellious laugh.

1953
01:49:44,111 --> 01:49:46,489
I was trying to change a laugh,

1954
01:49:46,563 --> 01:49:48,907
ramping up into a scream.
And it worked.

1955
01:49:49,016 --> 01:49:51,644
It was my proudest moment
at the whole preview.

1956
01:49:51,752 --> 01:49:53,652
They laughed when they heard "shit,"

1957
01:49:53,754 --> 01:49:56,530
and when the shark came out
that laugh sustained itself

1958
01:49:56,607 --> 01:49:59,292
into a humongous scream,
and popcorn went flying.

1959
01:49:59,393 --> 01:50:03,193
It was amazing, and it made
me greedy. I got so greedy.

1960
01:50:03,397 --> 01:50:05,388
Because earlier in the movie,

1961
01:50:05,933 --> 01:50:09,051
when they find Ben
Gardner's head in the boat,

1962
01:50:09,319 --> 01:50:12,550
I hadn't timed it right,
and Richard turns around…

1963
01:50:12,623 --> 01:50:14,364
That's where the head's already there,

1964
01:50:14,475 --> 01:50:16,842
and there was no reaction
from the audience at all.

1965
01:50:16,944 --> 01:50:19,208
So I was scratching my head
after the preview.

1966
01:50:19,313 --> 01:50:20,997
I was extraordinarily happy.

1967
01:50:21,064 --> 01:50:24,159
The numbers were the highest
numbers in Universal's history,

1968
01:50:24,251 --> 01:50:26,413
the executives were happy, we were happy,

1969
01:50:26,520 --> 01:50:28,010
the audience loved the picture.

1970
01:50:28,122 --> 01:50:29,203
And I was greedy.

1971
01:50:29,273 --> 01:50:32,265
I said, "There's one more
scream we can get into this movie

1972
01:50:32,342 --> 01:50:35,528
"if I can figure out this thing
with Ben Gardner's head."

1973
01:50:36,230 --> 01:50:39,382
The studio wouldn't give me more
money, though they were ecstatic.

1974
01:50:39,449 --> 01:50:43,158
They said, "It's fine. Don't fix
something that's not broken. It works.

1975
01:50:43,270 --> 01:50:46,388
"Don't mess with it, or you'll
improve this into a failure."

1976
01:50:46,456 --> 01:50:49,016
So I went and spent $3,000 of my own money

1977
01:50:49,193 --> 01:50:51,605
to have some art department people

1978
01:50:51,712 --> 01:50:54,613
build a balsa-wood side of a boat

1979
01:50:55,098 --> 01:50:57,442
to match the Ben Gardner
boat we had shot before,

1980
01:50:57,551 --> 01:51:01,351
cut a hole in it and got the
same Ben Gardner head,

1981
01:51:01,471 --> 01:51:04,372
the Styrofoam head, latex and Styrofoam,

1982
01:51:04,474 --> 01:51:05,987
and had it underwater.

1983
01:51:06,093 --> 01:51:09,620
And this time, simply, when the
double for Rick came to the hole,

1984
01:51:09,730 --> 01:51:12,461
I used several timings, I shot
it about nine different ways.

1985
01:51:12,566 --> 01:51:13,943
One time I shot it,

1986
01:51:14,017 --> 01:51:16,827
he comes through the hole
and the head comes out.

1987
01:51:17,104 --> 01:51:18,515
Another time,

1988
01:51:18,589 --> 01:51:21,058
he comes through the hole and
the head comes out at the same time.

1989
01:51:21,124 --> 01:51:24,651
Another time, the head comes
out and he's not even in the shot.

1990
01:51:24,761 --> 01:51:27,105
Then the camera goes
really close to the knife,

1991
01:51:27,214 --> 01:51:29,273
taking the tooth out,
the head comes out there.

1992
01:51:29,383 --> 01:51:31,750
I did it a whole bunch of different ways,

1993
01:51:31,852 --> 01:51:34,184
and then I went to the dubbing room.

1994
01:51:34,288 --> 01:51:37,770
We were already remixing
little changes we had made.

1995
01:51:38,325 --> 01:51:40,384
And I cut it in and I tried it out

1996
01:51:40,494 --> 01:51:42,553
on all of the sound effects editors,

1997
01:51:42,663 --> 01:51:44,757
the music editors and the dubbers.

1998
01:51:44,865 --> 01:51:46,765
And I showed them one way, and they said,

1999
01:51:46,867 --> 01:51:48,858
"Interesting. It's better
than what you had."

2000
01:51:48,969 --> 01:51:50,960
Another way, no reaction.

2001
01:51:51,205 --> 01:51:53,765
And then one way, nobody screamed,

2002
01:51:53,874 --> 01:51:55,501
but they all kind of suddenly said,

2003
01:51:55,609 --> 01:51:58,670
"Oh, yeah. Wow. That
surprised me. I didn't expect it."

2004
01:51:59,429 --> 01:52:01,147
It was simply a matter of timing.

2005
01:52:01,248 --> 01:52:02,875
And the moment that works the best,

2006
01:52:02,983 --> 01:52:05,896
which is the moment in the
movie that the dubbers reacted to,

2007
01:52:05,986 --> 01:52:08,830
is the moment where he gets to the hole,

2008
01:52:09,640 --> 01:52:12,883
and then the head comes out.
There's just a bit of a pause.

2009
01:52:22,069 --> 01:52:25,630
And I just remember we then
took the film to Long Beach.

2010
01:52:26,123 --> 01:52:28,535
I think at the Lakewood Theaters.

2011
01:52:29,243 --> 01:52:30,711
And we had a second preview there

2012
01:52:30,811 --> 01:52:33,496
with that extra scene,
that extra moment in.

2013
01:52:33,814 --> 01:52:36,442
And it got a humongous scream.

2014
01:52:36,867 --> 01:52:40,667
Bigger than the scream in Dallas when
the shark came out, with Roy chumming.

2015
01:52:40,737 --> 01:52:42,501
And popcorn flew even higher,

2016
01:52:42,572 --> 01:52:44,449
and people came out of their seats higher.

2017
01:52:44,558 --> 01:52:47,255
And I was thrilled until at Lakewood,

2018
01:52:47,561 --> 01:52:50,826
we got to the scene that
got the previous big laugh,

2019
01:52:51,098 --> 01:52:53,897
where the shark comes out of
the water when Roy's chumming.

2020
01:52:54,001 --> 01:52:57,369
It got a big scream, but it was only 50%

2021
01:52:57,938 --> 01:53:00,316
or less of the scream we got in Dallas.

2022
01:53:00,407 --> 01:53:02,569
So that preview was a smash preview.

2023
01:53:02,676 --> 01:53:06,112
The scores were higher, the
studio was flying on cloud nine.

2024
01:53:06,213 --> 01:53:08,910
They'll make a fortune with
the movie, they keep saying.

2025
01:53:09,016 --> 01:53:10,848
And I'm scratching my head thinking,

2026
01:53:10,951 --> 01:53:13,852
"Now what did I do to make
that second scream less?"

2027
01:53:13,954 --> 01:53:16,139
And I realized it was a no-brainer.

2028
01:53:16,690 --> 01:53:21,184
The audience didn't trust me after the
first scream at the end of the first act.

2029
01:53:21,295 --> 01:53:24,026
They were surprised, and
then they were looking out

2030
01:53:24,131 --> 01:53:26,975
for shadows and things
coming out from behind things.

2031
01:53:27,067 --> 01:53:31,504
And they were defensive and
ready for some kind of a shock.

2032
01:53:32,456 --> 01:53:36,916
The rating of Jaws was a real cliffhanger.

2033
01:53:38,045 --> 01:53:41,140
Richard Heffner, the
chairman of the rating board

2034
01:53:41,248 --> 01:53:43,683
of the Motion Picture
Association of America

2035
01:53:43,784 --> 01:53:47,152
that tells parents
what to expect on movies…

2036
01:53:48,322 --> 01:53:52,884
It was essential to the MCA/Universal
financiers and distributors

2037
01:53:53,260 --> 01:53:56,161
that Jaws get a "PG" rating,

2038
01:53:56,263 --> 01:53:59,164
meaning "parental guidance indicated,"

2039
01:53:59,266 --> 01:54:01,633
but it meant that children
could come and see it.

2040
01:54:01,735 --> 01:54:05,478
Whatever the ratings board said
to Sheinberg and Wasserman,

2041
01:54:06,289 --> 01:54:09,441
they told Dick and David, who
came to me as my producers

2042
01:54:09,543 --> 01:54:13,639
and said, "Steven, in order to get
not an 'R' rating, but a 'PG' rating,

2043
01:54:13,864 --> 01:54:17,346
"you need to cut some frames
from the leg coming down."

2044
01:54:17,451 --> 01:54:20,352
I was happy to do it, as they
didn't ask me to cut the leg out.

2045
01:54:20,454 --> 01:54:25,016
They just asked me not to let the
leg hit, bounce, gush blood, settle…

2046
01:54:25,208 --> 01:54:27,188
Because I was really sort of studying it.

2047
01:54:27,294 --> 01:54:30,264
So I cut about a foot and a
half to two feet off that shot.

2048
01:54:30,364 --> 01:54:32,992
<i>You'll see the leg.
Just when you see it severed</i>

2049
01:54:33,100 --> 01:54:35,899
<i>and it just starts to hit
the silt bed, we cut</i> away.

2050
01:54:35,986 --> 01:54:40,401
And finally, a "PG" was awarded.

2051
01:54:41,375 --> 01:54:45,619
Our argument was very simple
with Heffner and his board.

2052
01:54:46,630 --> 01:54:50,897
Nobody impersonates a shark,
unlike films of violence.

2053
01:54:51,168 --> 01:54:54,001
No one is going to get up
and eat somebody.

2054
01:54:54,121 --> 01:54:56,556
Nobody's going to drag
someone down in the water.

2055
01:54:56,640 --> 01:55:01,294
What happens in nature is
part of childhood's experience.

2056
01:55:01,395 --> 01:55:05,127
<i>Anyone</i> who's read <i>Grimm's
Fairy Tales… Red Riding Hood.</i>

2057
01:55:05,232 --> 01:55:08,964
<i>Little Red Riding Hood is one</i> of
<i>the scariest stories ever written,</i>

2058
01:55:10,337 --> 01:55:13,534
and children are regularly terrified.

2059
01:55:14,074 --> 01:55:16,338
After the film was distributed,

2060
01:55:16,877 --> 01:55:21,246
I don't recall any letters from children…

2061
01:55:21,348 --> 01:55:23,783
About children having bad dreams.

2062
01:55:24,151 --> 01:55:26,779
I had many about adults having bad dreams

2063
01:55:26,887 --> 01:55:29,083
and never going by the water again.

2064
01:55:29,306 --> 01:55:33,243
And so the rating, to the
great relief of MCA/Universal,

2065
01:55:33,310 --> 01:55:37,156
was, in my estimation, rightly
given "parental guidance."

2066
01:55:37,264 --> 01:55:41,724
"May be too intense for
some children" was on the ads.

2067
01:55:42,536 --> 01:55:45,050
Of course, all that did was bring them in.

2068
01:55:45,288 --> 01:55:48,531
I saw the film in its final version

2069
01:55:48,959 --> 01:55:51,690
when it played at the
Rivoli Theater in Manhattan,

2070
01:55:51,812 --> 01:55:54,895
which was a huge theater
with a great big screen.

2071
01:55:54,965 --> 01:55:59,334
And members of my family
and guests were invited.

2072
01:56:03,607 --> 01:56:07,817
Watching the audience react
to it was wonderfully exciting.

2073
01:56:07,928 --> 01:56:10,454
I mean, they just laughed
and they screamed.

2074
01:56:10,831 --> 01:56:13,277
They did everything
that we hoped they would do.

2075
01:56:13,350 --> 01:56:16,559
I happened, by coincidence, to be
next to the Newsweek researcher,

2076
01:56:16,670 --> 01:56:18,297
who was next to the Time researcher.

2077
01:56:18,405 --> 01:56:21,887
At the moment when Roy turns aft

2078
01:56:21,958 --> 01:56:23,619
and the shark comes out of the water,

2079
01:56:23,727 --> 01:56:26,207
and he utters that great
line that I wish I'd written,

2080
01:56:26,313 --> 01:56:28,554
"I think you're gonna need a bigger boat,"

2081
01:56:28,632 --> 01:56:30,930
<i>the Newsweek researcher
jumped out</i> of <i>her</i> chair

2082
01:56:31,001 --> 01:56:34,483
and landed on the upturned
pen of the Time researcher,

2083
01:56:34,588 --> 01:56:37,102
thus having a double screamer going.

2084
01:56:37,541 --> 01:56:39,475
I thought right then,

2085
01:56:39,543 --> 01:56:42,103
"We have a fairly successful
movie going on here."

2086
01:56:42,429 --> 01:56:45,012
There was applause at
the end of the movie.

2087
01:56:45,382 --> 01:56:48,010
The movie ends, we're
swimming away, it says "The End,"

2088
01:56:48,118 --> 01:56:51,110
and they went crackers.
Everyone went berserk.

2089
01:56:52,189 --> 01:56:54,317
However many people are in that theater…

2090
01:56:54,391 --> 01:56:57,509
I couldn't even tell you.
Pretty big theater.

2091
01:56:57,611 --> 01:56:59,124
They went nuts.

2092
01:57:01,831 --> 01:57:05,881
And then they sat and they
watched all of the credits,

2093
01:57:06,570 --> 01:57:09,915
every last one of them, and nobody moved.

2094
01:57:11,258 --> 01:57:13,886
And then they applauded again.

2095
01:57:13,994 --> 01:57:15,359
And I've never seen that.

2096
01:57:15,679 --> 01:57:19,411
And I remember walking out
on the sidewalk at the end of it.

2097
01:57:19,683 --> 01:57:22,243
I looked at Dreyfuss and he looked at me,

2098
01:57:22,319 --> 01:57:26,369
and he ran over and
he jumped up in my arms

2099
01:57:26,907 --> 01:57:30,787
and he said, "We're sensational!

2100
01:57:30,860 --> 01:57:32,624
"We're great!
We're terrific!"

2101
01:57:32,696 --> 01:57:34,255
And I said, "Yeah."

2102
01:57:34,331 --> 01:57:38,700
At the end of that evening I walked
out and I ran into Dreyfuss in the street,

2103
01:57:38,802 --> 01:57:40,429
and we went to a bar,

2104
01:57:40,503 --> 01:57:45,168
and all Rick could say was, "He did it!"

2105
01:57:45,859 --> 01:57:48,874
And I said, "Who did it?
What are you talking about?"

2106
01:57:48,979 --> 01:57:50,811
He said, "Spielberg
did it! He did it!"

2107
01:57:50,931 --> 01:57:52,660
It was a hell of a moment.

2108
01:57:52,766 --> 01:57:56,350
I felt so proud that I was in that movie,

2109
01:57:56,720 --> 01:57:58,814
and so proud for Spielberg.

2110
01:58:00,790 --> 01:58:03,942
I remember getting on
the phone with notes.

2111
01:58:04,044 --> 01:58:08,038
I was saying, "And you gotta
do this and you gotta do that."

2112
01:58:10,166 --> 01:58:11,634
He was very pleased.

2113
01:58:12,319 --> 01:58:16,313
Well, Jaws went on to become

2114
01:58:17,057 --> 01:58:20,368
the biggest picture of
all times at that time,

2115
01:58:21,478 --> 01:58:24,573
surpassing the $100 million mark,

2116
01:58:24,648 --> 01:58:27,015
which had never been done before.

2117
01:58:27,217 --> 01:58:30,960
And I remember Universal
marketing department

2118
01:58:31,755 --> 01:58:33,655
would take an ad out

2119
01:58:34,024 --> 01:58:37,221
with the shark and the titles

2120
01:58:37,294 --> 01:58:39,979
<i>of the various pictures that had beaten us</i>

2121
01:58:40,080 --> 01:58:41,491
<i>and held the records.</i>

2122
01:58:41,615 --> 01:58:45,495
<i>And the shark would
devour each one, each week,</i>

2123
01:58:45,619 --> 01:58:48,236
whether <i>it be</i> The Godfather
or The Sound of Music,

2124
01:58:48,305 --> 01:58:50,399
<i>finally</i> Gone With The Wind.

2125
01:58:50,657 --> 01:58:54,036
Until we were up on top
of the surface, number one,

2126
01:58:54,210 --> 01:58:57,987
and we became the
biggest picture of all time.

2127
01:58:58,632 --> 01:59:02,318
This was before even a
foreign release of any kind.

2128
01:59:02,419 --> 01:59:05,411
We busted right through
the $100 million mark.

2129
01:59:06,039 --> 01:59:10,317
And it was a phenomenon.
It really was a phenomenon.

2130
01:59:10,527 --> 01:59:13,371
When a movie has the
success that Jaws had,

2131
01:59:13,596 --> 01:59:16,258
it becomes more than an entertainment.

2132
01:59:16,333 --> 01:59:19,018
It becomes part of the popular culture.

2133
01:59:19,169 --> 01:59:20,432
And <i>Jaws</i> was no exception.

2134
01:59:20,537 --> 01:59:23,905
We had really wonderful
political cartoonists

2135
01:59:23,973 --> 01:59:26,499
like Conrad using the image of the shark

2136
01:59:26,910 --> 01:59:30,028
as a metaphor for political
behavior in Washington.

2137
01:59:30,130 --> 01:59:32,906
<i>We had sketches on Saturday Night Live.</i>

2138
01:59:32,982 --> 01:59:36,031
Chevy Chase did a great
Land Shark. I remember that.

2139
01:59:36,136 --> 01:59:39,436
And then John Belushi,
blessed be his memory,

2140
01:59:39,622 --> 01:59:43,286
did a fabulous impression of Dreyfuss.

2141
01:59:43,360 --> 01:59:46,762
You don't think of Belushi and
Dreyfuss being anywhere similar,

2142
01:59:46,830 --> 01:59:49,674
but when Belushi put on a
blue knit watch cap and said,

2143
01:59:49,783 --> 01:59:53,469
"This was no boating accident,"
you got a laugh out of it.

2144
01:59:55,004 --> 01:59:58,941
<i>The first shot of Airplane!</i>

2145
02:00:00,643 --> 02:00:03,305
By the Zucker brothers uses a shark theme.

2146
02:00:03,646 --> 02:00:07,640
It was a combination of elements
that were all so instantly identifiable

2147
02:00:07,751 --> 02:00:09,776
because everybody knew what they were.

2148
02:00:09,853 --> 02:00:13,096
The shark's theme became
a synonym for danger.

2149
02:00:15,842 --> 02:00:19,551
Just all those elements just
became part of popular culture.

2150
02:00:20,597 --> 02:00:21,860
Every time I'd fall asleep,

2151
02:00:21,965 --> 02:00:24,957
I dreamt I was on the third
or fourth day of shooting.

2152
02:00:25,301 --> 02:00:28,669
I'd wake up with an electrical
explosion in my brain.

2153
02:00:29,489 --> 02:00:31,537
My heart beating, can't catch my breath,

2154
02:00:31,608 --> 02:00:34,600
looking around the room,
where am I? Disoriented.

2155
02:00:34,978 --> 02:00:38,312
I'd calm down, get a glass of
water, go back to sleep again.

2156
02:00:38,782 --> 02:00:41,308
Same dream. I'm on
the fourth day of shooting,

2157
02:00:41,418 --> 02:00:46,106
and I know I've got another 146 days left.

2158
02:00:46,589 --> 02:00:48,421
And I'd wake up again.
Same thing.

2159
02:00:48,508 --> 02:00:52,695
And this thing was just haunting me
all night long till I didn't get any sleep.

2160
02:00:52,796 --> 02:00:57,745
So Jaws was a fun movie to
watch, but not a fun movie to make.
